# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: energy-management-system-building-management
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] High-profile applications of AI include advanced web search engines, chatbots, virtual assistants, autonomous vehicles, and play and analysis in strategy games (e.g., chess and Go).
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] Since the 2020s, generative AI has become widely available to generate images, audio, and videos from text prompts.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] The traditional goals of AI research include learning, reasoning, knowledge representation, planning, natural language processing, and perception, as well as support for robotics.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] To reach these goals, AI researchers have used techniques including state space search and mathematical optimization, formal logic, artificial neural networks, and methods based on statistics, operations research, and economics.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] AI also draws upon psychology, linguistics, philosophy, neuroscience, and other fields.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] Some companies, such as OpenAI, Google DeepMind and Meta, aim to create artificial general intelligence (AGI) – AI that can complete virtually any cognitive task at least as well as a human.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] Artificial intelligence was founded as an academic discipline in 1956, and the field went through multiple cycles of optimism throughout its history, followed by periods of disappointment and loss of funding, known as AI winters.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] Funding and interest increased substantially after 2012, when graphics processing units began being used to accelerate neural networks, and deep learning outperformed previous AI techniques.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] This growth accelerated further after 2017 with the transformer architecture.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] In the 2020s, an AI boom has coincided with advances in generative AI, which allowed for the creation and modification of media.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] In addition to AI safety and unintended consequences and harms from the use of AI, ethical concerns, AI's long-term effects, and potential existential risks have prompted discussions of AI regulation.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] The general problem of simulating (or creating) intelligence has been broken into subproblems.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] These consist of particular traits or capabilities that researchers expect an intelligent system to display.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] The traits described below have received the most attention and cover the scope of AI research.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] Early researchers developed algorithms that imitated step-by-step reasoning that humans use when they solve puzzles or make logical deductions.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] By the late 1980s and 1990s, methods were developed for dealing with uncertain or incomplete information, employing concepts from probability and economics.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] Many of these algorithms are insufficient for solving large reasoning problems because they experience a "combinatorial explosion": They become exponentially slower as the problems grow.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] Even humans rarely use the step-by-step deduction that early AI research could model.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] Humans solve most of their problems using fast, intuitive judgments.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] Reasoning models, a type of large language model trained to generate intermediate chains-of-thought, emerged in 2024 and allowed improved performance on complex problems in mathematics and coding.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] Knowledge representation and knowledge engineering allow AI programs to answer questions intelligently and make deductions about real-world facts.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] Formal knowledge representations are used in content-based indexing and retrieval, scene interpretation, clinical decision support, knowledge discovery (mining "interesting" and actionable inferences from large databases), and other areas.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] A knowledge base is a body of knowledge represented in a form that can be used by a program.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] An ontology is the set of objects, relations, concepts, and properties used by a particular domain of knowledge.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] There is also the difficulty of knowledge acquisition, the problem of obtaining knowledge for AI applications.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] An "agent" is any entity (artificial or not) that perceives and takes actions in the world.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] A rational agent has goals or preferences and takes actions to make them happen.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] In automated planning, the agent has a specific goal.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] In automated decision-making, the agent has preferences—there are some situations it would prefer to be in, and some situations it is trying to avoid.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] The decision-making agent assigns a number to each situation (called its "utility") that measures how much the agent prefers it.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] For each possible action, it can calculate the "expected utility": the utility of all possible outcomes of the action, weighted by the probability that the outcome will occur.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] It can then choose the action with the maximum expected utility.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] In classical planning, the agent knows exactly what the effect of any action will be.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] In most real-world problems, however, the agent may not be certain about the situation it is in (it is "unknown" or "unobservable") and it may not know for certain what will happen after each possible action (it is not "deterministic").
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] It must choose an action by making a probabilistic guess and then reassess the situation to see if the action worked.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] Alongside thorough testing and improvement based on previous decisions, having an explanation for why the agent took certain decisions is a way to build trust, especially when the decisions have to be relied upon.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] In some problems, the agent's preferences may be uncertain, especially if there are other agents or humans involved.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] These preferences be learned (e.g., with inverse reinforcement learning), or the agent can seek information to improve them.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] Information value theory can be used to weigh the value of exploratory or experimental actions.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] The space of possible future actions and situations is typically intractably large, so the agents must take actions and evaluate situations while being uncertain of what the outcome will be.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] A Markov decision process has a transition model that describes the probability that a particular action will change the state in a particular way and a reward function that supplies the utility of each state and the cost of each action.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] A policy associates a decision with each possible state.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] The policy could be calculated (e.g., by iteration), be heuristic, or it can be learned.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] Game theory describes the rational behavior of multiple interacting agents and is used in AI programs that make decisions that involve other agents.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] Machine learning is the study of programs that can improve their performance on a given task automatically.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] It has been a part of AI from the beginning.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] There are several kinds of machine learning.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] Unsupervised learning analyzes a stream of data and finds patterns and makes predictions without any other guidance.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] Supervised learning requires labeling the training data with the expected answers, and comes in two main varieties: classification (where the program must learn to predict what category the input belongs in) and regression (where the program must deduce a numeric function based on numeric input).
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] In reinforcement learning, the agent is rewarded for good responses and punished for bad ones.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] The agent learns to choose responses that are classified as "good".
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] Transfer learning is when the knowledge gained from one problem is applied to a new problem.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] Deep learning is a type of machine learning that runs inputs through biologically inspired artificial neural networks for all of these types of learning.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] Computational learning theory can assess learners by computational complexity, by sample complexity (how much data is required), or by other notions of optimization.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] Natural language processing (NLP) allows programs to read, write and communicate in human languages.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] Specific problems include speech recognition, speech synthesis, machine translation, information extraction, information retrieval and question answering.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] Early work, based on Noam Chomsky's generative grammar and semantic networks, had difficulty with word-sense disambiguation unless restricted to small domains called "micro-worlds" (due to the common sense knowledge problem).
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] Margaret Masterman believed that it was meaning and not grammar that was the key to understanding languages, and that thesauri and not dictionaries should be the basis of computational language structure.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] Modern deep learning techniques for NLP include word embedding (representing words, typically as vectors encoding their meaning), transformers (a deep learning architecture using an attention mechanism), and others.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] In 2019, generative pre-trained transformer (or "GPT") language models began to generate coherent text, and by 2023, these models were able to get human-level scores on the bar exam, SAT test, GRE test, and many other real-world applications.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] Machine perception is the ability to use input from sensors (such as cameras, microphones, wireless signals, active lidar, sonar, radar, and tactile sensors) to deduce aspects of the world.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] Computer vision is the ability to analyze visual input.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] The field includes speech recognition, image classification, facial recognition, object recognition, object tracking, and robotic perception.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] Affective computing is a field that comprises systems that recognize, interpret, process, or simulate human feeling, emotion, and mood.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] For example, some virtual assistants are programmed to speak conversationally or even to banter humorously; it makes them appear more sensitive to the emotional dynamics of human interaction, or to otherwise facilitate human–computer interaction.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] However, this tends to give naïve users an unrealistic conception of the intelligence of existing computer agents.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] Moderate successes related to affective computing include textual sentiment analysis and, more recently, multimodal sentiment analysis, wherein AI classifies the effects displayed by a videotaped subject.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] A machine with artificial general intelligence would be able to solve a wide variety of problems with breadth and versatility similar to human intelligence.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] AI research uses a wide variety of techniques to accomplish the goals above.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] State space search searches through a tree of possible states to try to find a goal state.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] For example, planning algorithms search through trees of goals and subgoals, attempting to find a path to a target goal, a process called means-ends analysis.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] Simple exhaustive searches are rarely sufficient for most real-world problems: the search space (the number of places to search) quickly grows to astronomical numbers.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] The result is a search that is too slow or never completes.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] "Heuristics" or "rules of thumb" can help prioritize choices that are more likely to reach a goal.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] Adversarial search is used for game-playing programs, such as chess or Go.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] It searches through a tree of possible moves and countermoves, looking for a winning position.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] Local search uses mathematical optimization to find a solution to a problem.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] It begins with some form of guess and refines it incrementally.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] Gradient descent is a type of local search that optimizes a set of numerical parameters by incrementally adjusting them to minimize a loss function.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] Variants of gradient descent are commonly used to train neural networks, through the backpropagation algorithm.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] Another type of local search is evolutionary computation, which aims to iteratively improve a set of candidate solutions by "mutating" and "recombining" them, selecting only the fittest to survive each generation.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] Distributed search processes can coordinate via swarm intelligence algorithms.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] Two popular swarm algorithms used in search are particle swarm optimization (inspired by bird flocking) and ant colony optimization (inspired by ant trails).
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] Formal logic is used for reasoning and knowledge representation.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] Deductive reasoning in logic is the process of proving a new statement (conclusion) from other statements that are given and assumed to be true (the premises).
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] Proofs can be structured as proof trees, in which nodes are labelled by sentences, and children nodes are connected to parent nodes by inference rules.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] Given a problem and a set of premises, problem-solving reduces to searching for a proof tree whose root node is labelled by a solution of the problem and whose leaf nodes are labelled by premises or axioms.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] In the case of Horn clauses, problem-solving search can be performed by reasoning forwards from the premises or backwards from the problem.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] In the more general case of the clausal form of first-order logic, resolution is a single, axiom-free rule of inference, in which a problem is solved by proving a contradiction from premises that include the negation of the problem to be solved.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] Inference in both Horn clause logic and first-order logic is undecidable, and therefore intractable.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] However, backward reasoning with Horn clauses, which underpins computation in the logic programming language Prolog, is Turing complete.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] Moreover, its efficiency is competitive with computation in other symbolic programming languages.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] Fuzzy logic assigns a "degree of truth" between 0 and 1.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] It can therefore handle propositions that are vague and partially true.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] Non-monotonic logics, including logic programming with negation as failure, are designed to handle default reasoning.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] Other specialized versions of logic have been developed to describe many complex domains.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] Many problems in AI (including reasoning, planning, learning, perception, and robotics) require the agent to operate with incomplete or uncertain information.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] AI researchers have devised a number of tools to solve these problems using methods from probability theory and economics.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] Precise mathematical tools have been developed that analyze how an agent can make choices and plan, using decision theory, decision analysis, and information value theory.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] These tools include models such as Markov decision processes, dynamic decision networks, game theory and mechanism design.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] Bayesian networks are a tool that can be used for reasoning (using the Bayesian inference algorithm), learning (using the expectation–maximization algorithm), planning (using decision networks) and perception (using dynamic Bayesian networks).
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] Probabilistic algorithms can also be used for filtering, prediction, smoothing, and finding explanations for streams of data, thus helping perception systems analyze processes that occur over time (e.g., hidden Markov models or Kalman filters).
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] The simplest AI applications can be divided into two types: classifiers (e.g., "if shiny then diamond"), on one hand, and controllers (e.g., "if diamond then pick up"), on the other hand.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] Classifiers are functions that use pattern matching to determine the closest match.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] They can be fine-tuned based on chosen examples using supervised learning.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] Each pattern (also called an "observation") is labeled with a certain predefined class.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] All the observations combined with their class labels are known as a data set.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] When a new observation is received, that observation is classified based on previous experience.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] There are many kinds of classifiers in use.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] The decision tree is the simplest and most widely used symbolic machine learning algorithm.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] K-nearest neighbor algorithm was the most widely used analogical AI until the mid-1990s, and Kernel methods such as the support vector machine (SVM) displaced k-nearest neighbor in the 1990s.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] The naive Bayes classifier is reportedly the "most widely used learner" at Google, due in part to its scalability.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] Neural networks are also used as classifiers.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] An artificial neural network is based on a collection of nodes also known as artificial neurons, which loosely model the neurons in a biological brain.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] It is trained to recognise patterns; once trained, it can recognise those patterns in fresh data.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] There is an input, at least one hidden layer of nodes and an output.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] Each node applies a function and once the weight crosses its specified threshold, the data is transmitted to the next layer.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] A network is typically called a deep neural network if it has at least 2 hidden layers.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] Learning algorithms for neural networks use local search to choose the weights that will get the right output for each input during training.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] The most common training technique is the backpropagation algorithm.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] Neural networks learn to model complex relationships between inputs and outputs and find patterns in data.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] In theory, a neural network can learn any function.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] In feedforward neural networks the signal passes in only one direction.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] The term perceptron typically refers to a single-layer neural network.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] In contrast, deep learning uses many layers.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] Recurrent neural networks (RNNs) feed the output signal back into the input, which allows short-term memories of previous input events.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] Long short-term memory networks (LSTMs) are recurrent neural networks that better preserve longterm dependencies and are less sensitive to the vanishing gradient problem.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] Convolutional neural networks (CNNs) use layers of kernels to more efficiently process local patterns.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] This local processing is especially important in image processing, where the early CNN layers typically identify simple local patterns such as edges and curves, with subsequent layers detecting more complex patterns like textures, and eventually whole objects.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] Deep learning uses several layers of neurons between the network's inputs and outputs.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] The multiple layers can progressively extract higher-level features from the raw input.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] For example, in image processing, lower layers may identify edges, while higher layers may identify the concepts relevant to a human such as digits, letters, or faces.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] Deep learning has profoundly improved the performance of programs in many important subfields of artificial intelligence, including computer vision, speech recognition, natural language processing, image classification, and others.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] The reason that deep learning performs so well in so many applications is not known as of 2021.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] Generative pre-trained transformers (GPT) are large language models (LLMs) that generate text based on the semantic relationships between words in sentences.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] Text-based GPT models are pre-trained on a large corpus of text that can be from the Internet.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] The pretraining consists of predicting the next token (a token being usually a word, subword, or punctuation).
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] Throughout this pretraining, GPT models accumulate knowledge about the world and can then generate human-like text by repeatedly predicting the next token.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] Typically, a subsequent training phase makes the model more truthful, useful, and harmless, usually with a technique called reinforcement learning from human feedback (RLHF).
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] Current GPT models are prone to generating falsehoods called "hallucinations".
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] These can be reduced with RLHF and quality data, but the problem has been getting worse for reasoning systems.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] Such systems are used in chatbots, which allow people to ask a question or request a task in simple text.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] Current models and services include ChatGPT, Claude, Gemini, Copilot, and Meta AI.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] Multimodal GPT models can process different types of data (modalities) such as images, videos, sound, and text.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] Specialized programming languages such as Prolog were used in early AI research, but general-purpose programming languages like Python have become predominant.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] The transistor density in integrated circuits has been observed to roughly double every 18 months—a trend known as Moore's law, named after the Intel co-founder Gordon Moore, who first identified it.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] Improvements in GPUs have been even faster, a trend sometimes called Huang's law, named after Nvidia co-founder and CEO Jensen Huang.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] The deployment of AI may be overseen by a chief automation officer (CAO).
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] AlphaFold 2 (2021) demonstrated the ability to approximate, in hours rather than months, the 3D structure of a protein.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] In 2023, it was reported that AI-guided drug discovery helped find a class of antibiotics capable of killing two different types of drug-resistant bacteria.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] In 2024, researchers used machine learning to accelerate the search for Parkinson's disease drug treatments.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] Their aim was to identify compounds that block the clumping, or aggregation, of alpha-synuclein (the protein that characterises Parkinson's disease).
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] They were able to speed up the initial screening process ten-fold and reduce the cost by a thousand-fold.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] AI is increasingly being used in medical diagnostics, including the detection of diseases such as lung cancer from medical imaging like CT scans.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] A 2026 *Nature* article titled "Dozens of AI disease-prediction models were trained on dubious data" highlighted the use of unreliable data being used to train AI medical prediction models for stroke and diabetes in 125 research articles.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] Evidence suggested some of the AI tools that were developed on unreliable data had been used on patients, although it was not clear if there were adverse outcomes.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] Game playing programs have been used since the 1950s to demonstrate and test AI's most advanced techniques.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] Deep Blue became the first computer chess-playing system to beat a reigning world chess champion, Garry Kasparov, on 11 May 1997.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] In 2011, in a *Jeopardy!* quiz show exhibition match, IBM's question answering system, Watson, defeated the two greatest *Jeopardy!* champions, Brad Rutter and Ken Jennings, by a significant margin.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] In March 2016, AlphaGo won 4 out of 5 games of Go in a match with Go champion Lee Sedol, becoming the first computer Go-playing system to beat a professional Go player without handicaps.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] Then, in 2017, it defeated Ke Jie, who was the best Go player in the world.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] Other programs handle imperfect-information games, such as the poker-playing program Pluribus.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] DeepMind developed increasingly generalistic reinforcement learning models, such as with MuZero, which could be trained to play chess, Go, or Atari games.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] In 2019, DeepMind's AlphaStar achieved grandmaster level in StarCraft II, a particularly challenging real-time strategy game that involves incomplete knowledge of what happens on the map.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] In 2021, an AI agent competed in a PlayStation Gran Turismo competition, winning against four of the world's best Gran Turismo drivers using deep reinforcement learning.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] In 2024, Google DeepMind introduced SIMA, a type of AI capable of autonomously playing nine previously unseen open-world video games by observing screen output, as well as executing short, specific tasks in response to natural language instructions.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] In mathematics, probabilistic large language models are versatile, but can also produce wrong answers in the form of hallucinations.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] The Alibaba Group developed a version of its *Qwen* models called *Qwen2-Math*, that achieved state-of-the-art performance on several mathematical benchmarks, including 84% accuracy on the MATH dataset of competition mathematics problems.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] In January 2025, Microsoft proposed the technique *rStar-Math* that leverages Monte Carlo tree search and step-by-step reasoning, enabling a relatively small language model like *Qwen-7B* to solve 53% of the AIME 2024 and 90% of the MATH benchmark problems.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] When natural language is used to describe mathematical problems, converters can transform such prompts into a formal language such as Lean to define mathematical tasks.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] The experimental model *Gemini Deep Think* accepts natural language prompts directly and achieved gold medal results in the International Math Olympiad of 2025.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] Topological deep learning integrates various topological approaches.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] According to Nicolas Firzli, director of the World Pensions & Investments Forum, it may be too early to see the emergence of highly innovative AI-informed financial products and services.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] Various countries are deploying AI military applications.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] The main applications enhance command and control, communications, sensors, integration and interoperability.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] Research is targeting intelligence collection and analysis, logistics, cyber operations, information operations, and semiautonomous and autonomous vehicles.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] AI technologies enable coordination of sensors and effectors, threat detection and identification, marking of enemy positions, target acquisition, coordination and deconfliction of distributed Joint Fires between networked combat vehicles, both human-operated and autonomous.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] AI has been used in military operations in Iraq, Syria, Israel and Ukraine.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] Generative artificial intelligence (GenAI) is a subfield of artificial intelligence (AI) that uses generative models to generate text, images, videos, audio, software code (vibe coding) or other forms of data.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] These models learn the underlying patterns and structures of their training data, and use them to generate new data in response to input, which often takes the form of natural language prompts.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] The prevalence of generative AI tools has increased significantly since the AI boom in the 2020s.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] This boom was made possible by improvements in deep neural networks, particularly large language models (LLMs), which are based on the transformer architecture.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] Generative AI applications include chatbots such as ChatGPT, Claude, Copilot, DeepSeek, Doubao, Google Gemini, Grok and Qwen; text-to-image models such as DALL-E, Firefly, Stable Diffusion, and Midjourney; and text-to-video models such as Veo, LTX and Sora.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] Companies in a variety of sectors have used generative AI, including those in software development, healthcare, finance, entertainment, customer service, sales and marketing, art, writing, and product design.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] AI agents are software entities designed to perceive their environment, make decisions, and take actions autonomously to achieve specific goals.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] These agents can interact with users, their environment, or other agents.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] AI agents are used in various applications, including virtual assistants, chatbots, autonomous vehicles, game-playing systems, and industrial robotics.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] AI agents operate within the constraints of their programming, available computational resources, and hardware limitations.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] This means they are restricted to performing tasks within their defined scope and have finite memory and processing capabilities.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] In real-world applications, AI agents often face time constraints for decision-making and action execution.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] Many AI agents incorporate learning algorithms, enabling them to improve their performance over time through experience or training.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] Using machine learning, AI agents can adapt to new situations and optimise their behaviour for their designated tasks.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] Microsoft introduced Copilot Search in February 2023 under the name Bing Chat.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] Copilot Search provides AI-generated summaries.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] Google introduced an AI Mode at its Google I/O event on 20 May 2025.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] Applications of AI in this domain include AI-enabled menstruation and fertility trackers that analyze user data to offer predictions, AI-integrated sex toys (e.g., teledildonics), AI-generated sexual education content, and AI agents that simulate sexual and romantic partners (e.g., Replika).
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] AI is also used for the production of non-consensual deepfake pornography, raising significant ethical and legal concerns.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] AI technologies have also been used to attempt to identify online gender-based violence and online sexual grooming of minors.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] In a 2017 survey, one in five companies reported having incorporated "AI" in some offerings or processes.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] In the field of evacuation and disaster management, AI has been used to investigate patterns in large-scale and small-scale evacuations using historical data from GPS, videos or social media.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] During the 2024 Indian elections, US$50 million was spent on authorized AI-generated content, notably by creating deepfakes of allied (including sometimes deceased) politicians to better engage with voters, and by translating speeches to various local languages.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] The use of generative AI by law firms for legal research resulted in the creation of the global "AI Hallucination Cases" database, in April 2025, established by HEC Paris and Sciences Po legal data analysis lecturer Damien Charlotin.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p01] By 2026, judges had issued sanctions and bar associations had issued warnings due to attorney submissions to the courts containing fabricated case law citations hallucinated by AI tools.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] AI has potential benefits and potential risks.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] AI may be able to advance science and find solutions for serious problems: Demis Hassabis of DeepMind hopes to "solve intelligence, and then use that to solve everything else".
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] However, as the use of AI has become widespread, several unintended consequences and risks have been identified.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] In-production systems can sometimes not factor ethics and bias into their AI training processes, especially when the AI algorithms are inherently unexplainable in deep learning.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] Machine learning algorithms require large amounts of data.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] The techniques used to acquire this data have raised concerns about privacy, surveillance and copyright.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] AI-powered devices and services, such as virtual assistants and IoT products, continuously collect personal information, raising concerns about intrusive data gathering and unauthorized access by third parties.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] The loss of privacy is further exacerbated by AI's ability to process and combine vast amounts of data, potentially leading to a surveillance society where individual activities are constantly monitored and analyzed without adequate safeguards or transparency.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] Sensitive user data collected may include online activity records, geolocation data, video, or audio.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] For example, in order to build speech recognition algorithms, Amazon has recorded millions of private conversations and allowed temporary workers to listen to and transcribe some of them.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] Opinions about this widespread surveillance range from those who see it as a necessary evil to those for whom it is clearly unethical and a violation of the right to privacy.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] AI developers argue that this is the only way to deliver valuable applications and have developed several techniques that attempt to preserve privacy while still obtaining the data, such as data aggregation, de-identification and differential privacy.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] Since 2016, some privacy experts, such as Cynthia Dwork, have begun to view privacy in terms of fairness.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] Generative AI is often trained on unlicensed copyrighted works, including in domains such as images or computer code; the output is then used under the rationale of "fair use".
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] Experts disagree about how well and under what circumstances this rationale will hold up in courts of law; relevant factors may include "the purpose and character of the use of the copyrighted work" and "the effect upon the potential market for the copyrighted work".
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] Website owners can indicate that they do not want their content scraped via a "robots.txt" file.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] However, some companies will scrape content regardless because the robots.txt file has no real authority.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] In 2023, leading authors (including John Grisham and Jonathan Franzen) sued AI companies for using their work to train generative AI.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] Another discussed approach is to envision a separate *sui generis* system of protection for creations generated by AI to ensure fair attribution and compensation for human authors.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] The commercial AI scene is dominated by Big Tech companies such as Alphabet Inc., Amazon, Apple Inc., Meta Platforms, and Microsoft.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] Some of these players already own the vast majority of existing cloud infrastructure and computing power from data centers, allowing them to entrench further in the marketplace.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] Technology companies have built electricity and artificial intelligence infrastructure to facilitate the AI boom of the 2020s.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] A 2025 report from the consulting firm McKinsey & Company estimated that by 2030, $2.7 trillion would be invested into AI infrastructure and data centers in the US, surpassing World War II's Manhattan Project every month.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] In January 2024, the International Energy Agency (IEA) released *Electricity 2024, Analysis and Forecast to 2026*.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] This is the first IEA report to make projections for data centers and power consumption by AI and cryptocurrency.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] The report states that power demand for these uses might double by 2026, with the additional power consumption equaling that of Japan.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] Power consumption by AI is responsible for an increase in fossil fuel use, and has delayed closings of obsolete, carbon-emitting coal energy facilities.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] A ChatGPT search involves the use of 10 times the electrical energy as a Google search.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] Data centers' need for more and more electrical power is such that they might max out the electrical grid.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] The Big Tech companies counter that AI can be used to maximize the utilization of the grid by all.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] In 2024, *The Wall Street Journal* reported that big AI companies have begun negotiations with the US nuclear power providers to provide electricity to the data centers.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] In March 2024 Amazon purchased a Pennsylvania nuclear-powered data center for US$650 million.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] In September 2024, Microsoft announced an agreement with Constellation Energy to re-open the Three Mile Island nuclear power plant to provide Microsoft with 100% of all electric power produced by the plant for 20 years.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] Reopening the plant, which suffered a partial nuclear meltdown of its Unit 2 reactor in 1979, will require Constellation to get through strict regulatory processes which will include extensive safety scrutiny from the US Nuclear Regulatory Commission.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] If approved (this will be the first ever US re-commissioning of a nuclear plant), over 835 megawatts of power – enough for 800,000 homes – of energy will be produced.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] The cost for re-opening and upgrading is estimated at US$1.6 billion and is dependent on tax breaks for nuclear power contained in the 2022 US Inflation Reduction Act.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] As of 2024, the US government and the state of Michigan have been investing almost US$2 billion to reopen the Palisades Nuclear reactor on Lake Michigan.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] Closed since 2022, the plant was planned to be reopened in October 2025.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] After the last approval in September 2023, Taiwan suspended the approval of data centers north of Taoyuan with a capacity of more than 5 MW in 2024, due to power supply shortages.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] Taiwan aims to phase out nuclear power by 2025.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] Singapore imposed a ban on the opening of data centers in 2019 due to electric power, but in 2022, lifted this ban.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] On 1 November 2024, the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission (FERC) rejected an application submitted by Talen Energy for approval to supply some electricity from the nuclear power station Susquehanna to Amazon's data center.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] According to the Commission Chairman Willie L.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] Phillips, it is a burden on the electricity grid as well as a significant cost shifting concern to households and other business sectors.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] In 2025, a report prepared by the IEA estimated the greenhouse gas emissions from the energy consumption of AI at 180 million tons.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] By 2035, these emissions could rise to 300–500 million tonnes depending on what measures will be taken.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] This is below 1.5% of the energy sector emissions.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] The emissions reduction potential of AI was estimated at 5% of the energy sector emissions, but rebound effects (for example if people switch from public transport to autonomous cars) can reduce it.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] YouTube, Facebook and others use recommender systems to guide users to more content.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] These AI programs were given the goal of maximizing user engagement (that is, the only goal was to keep people watching).
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] The AI learned that users tended to choose misinformation, conspiracy theories, and extreme partisan content, and, to keep them watching, the AI recommended more of it.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] Users also tended to watch more content on the same subject, so the AI led people into filter bubbles where they received multiple versions of the same misinformation.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] This convinced many users that the misinformation was true, and ultimately undermined trust in institutions, the media and the government.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] The AI program had correctly learned to maximize its goal, but the result was harmful to society.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] After the U.S. election in 2016, major technology companies took some steps to mitigate the problem.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] In the early 2020s, generative AI began to create images, audio, and texts that are virtually indistinguishable from real photographs, recordings, or human writing, while realistic AI-generated videos became feasible in the mid-2020s.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] It is possible for bad actors to use this technology to create massive amounts of misinformation and computational propaganda through techniques such as deepfakes.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] AI pioneer and Nobel Prize-winning computer scientist Geoffrey Hinton expressed concern about AI enabling "authoritarian leaders to manipulate their electorates" on a large scale, among other risks.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] The ability to influence electorates has been proved in at least one study.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] This same study shows more inaccurate statements from the models when they advocate for candidates of the political right.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] AI researchers at Microsoft, OpenAI, universities and other organisations have suggested using "personhood credentials" as a way to overcome online deception enabled by AI models.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] Machine learning applications can be biased if they learn from biased data.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] The developers may not be aware that the bias exists.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] Discriminatory behavior by some LLMs can be observed in their output.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] Bias can be introduced by the way training data is selected and by the way a model is deployed.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] If a biased algorithm is used to make decisions that can seriously harm people (as it can in medicine, finance, recruitment, housing or policing) then the algorithm may cause discrimination.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] The field of fairness studies how to prevent harms from algorithmic biases.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] On 28 June 2015, Google Photos's new image labeling feature mistakenly identified Jacky Alcine and a friend as "gorillas" because they were black.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] The system was trained on a dataset that contained very few images of black people, a problem called "sample size disparity".
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] Google "fixed" this problem by preventing the system from labelling *anything* as a "gorilla".
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] Eight years later, in 2023, Google Photos still could not identify a gorilla, and neither could similar products from Apple, Facebook, Microsoft and Amazon.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] COMPAS is a commercial program widely used by U.S. courts to assess the likelihood of a defendant becoming a recidivist.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] In 2016, Julia Angwin at ProPublica discovered that COMPAS exhibited racial bias, despite the fact that the program was not told the races of the defendants.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] Although the error rate for both whites and blacks was calibrated equal at exactly 61%, the errors for each race were different—the system consistently overestimated the chance that a black person would re-offend and would underestimate the chance that a white person would not re-offend.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] In 2017, several researchers showed that it was mathematically impossible for COMPAS to accommodate all possible measures of fairness when the base rates of re-offense were different for whites and blacks in the data.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] A program can make biased decisions even if the data does not explicitly mention a problematic feature (such as "race" or "gender").
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] The feature will correlate with other features (like "address", "shopping history" or "first name"), and the program will make the same decisions based on these features as it would on "race" or "gender".
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] Criticism of COMPAS highlighted that machine learning models are designed to make "predictions" that are only valid if we assume that the future will resemble the past.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] If they are trained on data that includes the results of racist decisions in the past, machine learning models must predict that racist decisions will be made in the future.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] If an application then uses these predictions as *recommendations*, some of these "recommendations" will likely be racist.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] Thus, machine learning is not well suited to help make decisions in areas where there is hope that the future will be *better* than the past.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] It is descriptive rather than prescriptive.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] Bias and unfairness may go undetected because the developers are overwhelmingly white and male: among AI engineers, about 4% are black and 20% are women.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] There are various conflicting definitions and mathematical models of fairness.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] These notions depend on ethical assumptions, and are influenced by beliefs about society.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] One broad category is distributive fairness, which focuses on the outcomes, often identifying groups and seeking to compensate for statistical disparities.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] Representational fairness tries to ensure that AI systems do not reinforce negative stereotypes or render certain groups invisible.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] Procedural fairness focuses on the decision process rather than the outcome.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] The most relevant notions of fairness may depend on the context, notably the type of AI application and the stakeholders.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] The subjectivity in the notions of bias and fairness makes it difficult for companies to operationalize them.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] Having access to sensitive attributes such as race or gender is also considered by many AI ethicists to be necessary in order to compensate for biases, but it may conflict with anti-discrimination laws.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] At the 2022 ACM Conference on Fairness, Accountability, and Transparency a paper reported that a CLIP‑based (Contrastive Language-Image Pre-training) robotic system reproduced harmful gender‑ and race‑linked stereotypes in a simulated manipulation task.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] Many AI systems are so complex that their designers cannot explain how they reach their decisions.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] Particularly with deep neural networks, in which there are many non-linear relationships between inputs and outputs.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] But some popular explainability techniques exist.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] It is impossible to be certain that a program is operating correctly if no one knows how exactly it works.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] There have been many cases where a machine learning program passed rigorous tests, but nevertheless learned something different than what the programmers intended.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] For example, a system that could identify skin diseases better than medical professionals was found to actually have a strong tendency to classify images with a ruler as "cancerous", because pictures of malignancies typically include a ruler to show the scale.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] Another machine learning system designed to help effectively allocate medical resources was found to classify patients with asthma as being at "low risk" of dying from pneumonia.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] Having asthma is actually a severe risk factor, but since the patients having asthma would usually get much more medical care, they were relatively unlikely to die according to the training data.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] The correlation between asthma and low risk of dying from pneumonia was real, but misleading.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] People who have been harmed by an algorithm's decision have a right to an explanation.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] Doctors, for example, are expected to clearly and completely explain to their colleagues the reasoning behind any decision they make.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] Early drafts of the European Union's General Data Protection Regulation in 2016 included an explicit statement that this right exists.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] Industry experts noted that this is an unsolved problem with no solution in sight.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] Regulators argued that nevertheless the harm is real: if the problem has no solution, the tools should not be used.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] DARPA established the XAI ("Explainable Artificial Intelligence") program in 2014 to try to solve these problems.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] Several approaches aim to address the transparency problem.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] SHAP enables to visualise the contribution of each feature to the output.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] LIME can locally approximate a model's outputs with a simpler, interpretable model.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] Multitask learning provides a large number of outputs in addition to the target classification.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] These other outputs can help developers deduce what the network has learned.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] Deconvolution, DeepDream and other generative methods can allow developers to see what different layers of a deep network for computer vision have learned, and produce output that can suggest what the network is learning.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] For generative pre-trained transformers, Anthropic developed a technique based on dictionary learning that associates patterns of neuron activations with human-understandable concepts.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] Artificial intelligence provides a number of tools that are useful to bad actors, such as authoritarian governments, terrorists, criminals or rogue states.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] A lethal autonomous weapon is a machine that locates, selects and engages human targets without human supervision.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] Widely available AI tools can be used by bad actors to develop inexpensive autonomous weapons and, if produced at scale, they are potentially weapons of mass destruction.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] Even when used in conventional warfare, they currently cannot reliably choose targets and could potentially kill an innocent person.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] In 2014, 30 nations (including China) supported a ban on autonomous weapons under the United Nations' Convention on Certain Conventional Weapons, however the United States and others disagreed.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] By 2015, over fifty countries were reported to be researching battlefield robots.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] AI tools make it easier for authoritarian governments to efficiently control their citizens in several ways.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] Face and voice recognition allow widespread surveillance.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] Machine learning, operating this data, can classify potential enemies of the state and prevent them from hiding.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] Recommendation systems can precisely target propaganda and misinformation for maximum effect.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] Deepfakes and generative AI aid in producing misinformation.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] Advanced AI can make authoritarian centralized decision-making more competitive than liberal and decentralized systems such as markets.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] It lowers the cost and difficulty of digital warfare and advanced spyware.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] All these technologies have been available since 2020 or earlier—AI facial recognition systems are already being used for mass surveillance in China.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] There are many other ways in which AI is expected to help bad actors, some of which can not be foreseen.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] For example, machine-learning AI is able to design tens of thousands of toxic molecules in a matter of hours.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] Economists have frequently highlighted the risks of redundancies from AI, and speculated about unemployment if there is no adequate social policy for full employment.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] In the past, technology has tended to increase rather than reduce total employment, but economists acknowledge that "we're in uncharted territory" with AI.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] A survey of economists showed disagreement about whether the increasing use of robots and AI will cause a substantial increase in long-term unemployment, but they generally agree that it could be a net benefit if productivity gains are redistributed.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] Risk estimates vary; for example, in the 2010s, Michael Osborne and Carl Benedikt Frey estimated 47% of U.S. jobs are at "high risk" of potential automation, while an OECD report classified only 9% of U.S. jobs as "high risk".
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] The methodology of speculating about future employment levels has been criticised as lacking evidential foundation, and for implying that technology, rather than social policy, creates unemployment, as opposed to redundancies.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] In April 2023, it was reported that 70% of the jobs for Chinese video game illustrators had been eliminated by generative artificial intelligence.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] Early-career workers showed decreasing employment rates in some AI-exposed occupations.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] Unlike previous waves of automation, many middle-class jobs may be eliminated by artificial intelligence; *The Economist* stated in 2015 that "the worry that AI could do to white-collar jobs what steam power did to blue-collar ones during the Industrial Revolution" is "worth taking seriously".
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] Jobs at extreme risk range from paralegals to fast food cooks, while job demand is likely to increase for care-related professions ranging from personal healthcare to the clergy.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] With the increase of loneliness in the early 21st century, AI is sometimes identified as a potential source of relief to this problem.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] It would be possible, via human-like qualities built into AI products, for individuals to assume that this need can be met by artificial means.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] In some cases, people approach artificial intelligence for companionship when they believe that they would not find acceptance due to feeling outcast.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] Examples of harm coming to humans from advanced chatbots have been reported in courts in the United States, with AI companies accused of creating products that endanger humans through emotional confusion or deception.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] Recent public debates in artificial intelligence have increasingly focused on its broader societal and ethical implications.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] It has been argued AI will become so powerful that humanity may irreversibly lose control of it.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] This could, as physicist Stephen Hawking stated, "spell the end of the human race".
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] This scenario has been common in science fiction, when a computer or robot suddenly develops a human-like "self-awareness" (or "sentience" or "consciousness") and becomes a malevolent character.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] These sci-fi scenarios are misleading in several ways.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] First, AI does not require human-like sentience to be an existential risk.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] Modern AI programs are given specific goals and use learning and intelligence to achieve them.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] Philosopher Nick Bostrom argued that if one gives *almost any* goal to a sufficiently powerful AI, it may choose to destroy humanity to achieve it (he used the example of an automated paperclip factory that destroys the world to get more iron for paperclips).
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] Second, Yuval Noah Harari argues that AI does not require a robot body or physical control to pose an existential risk.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] The essential parts of civilization are not physical.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] Things like ideologies, law, government, money and the economy are built on language; they exist because there are stories that billions of people believe.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] The current prevalence of misinformation suggests that an AI could use language to convince people to believe anything, even to take actions that are destructive.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] Geoffrey Hinton said in 2025 that modern AI is particularly "good at persuasion" and getting better all the time.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] He asks, "Suppose you wanted to invade the capital of the US.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] Do you have to go there and do it yourself?
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] The opinions amongst experts and industry insiders are mixed, with sizable fractions both concerned and unconcerned by risk from eventual superintelligent AI.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] Personalities such as Stephen Hawking, Bill Gates, and Elon Musk, as well as AI pioneers such as Geoffrey Hinton, Yoshua Bengio, Stuart Russell, Demis Hassabis, and Sam Altman, have expressed concerns about existential risk from AI.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] In May 2023, Geoffrey Hinton announced his resignation from Google in order to be able to "freely speak out about the risks of AI" without "considering how this impacts Google".
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] He notably mentioned risks of an AI takeover, and stressed that in order to avoid the worst outcomes, establishing safety guidelines will require cooperation among those competing in use of AI.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] In 2023, many leading AI experts endorsed the joint statement that "Mitigating the risk of extinction from AI should be a global priority alongside other societal-scale risks such as pandemics and nuclear war".
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] Some other researchers were more optimistic.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] However, after 2016, the study of current and future risks and possible solutions became a serious area of research.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] Friendly AI are machines that have been designed from the beginning to minimize risks and to make choices that benefit humans.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] Eliezer Yudkowsky, who coined the term, argues that developing friendly AI should be a higher research priority: it may require a large investment and it must be completed before AI becomes an existential risk.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] Machines with intelligence have the potential to use their intelligence to make ethical decisions.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] The field of machine ethics provides machines with ethical principles and procedures for resolving ethical dilemmas.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] The field of machine ethics is also called computational morality, and was founded at an AAAI symposium in 2005.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] Other approaches include Wendell Wallach's "artificial moral agents" and Stuart J.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] Russell's three principles for developing provably beneficial machines.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] Active organizations in the AI open-source community include Hugging Face, Google, EleutherAI and Meta.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] Various AI models, such as Llama 2, Mistral or Stable Diffusion, have been made open-weight, meaning that their architecture and trained parameters (the "weights") are publicly available.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] Open-weight models can be freely fine-tuned, which allows companies to specialize them with their own data and for their own use-case.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] Open-weight models are useful for research and innovation but can also be misused.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] Since they can be fine-tuned, any built-in security measure, such as objecting to harmful requests, can be trained away until it becomes ineffective.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] Some researchers warn that future AI models may develop dangerous capabilities (such as the potential to drastically facilitate bioterrorism) and that once released on the Internet, they cannot be deleted everywhere if needed.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] They recommend pre-release audits and cost-benefit analyses.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] Artificial intelligence projects can be guided by ethical considerations during the design, development, and implementation of an AI system.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] The UK AI Safety Institute released in 2024 a testing toolset called 'Inspect' for AI safety evaluations available under an MIT open-source licence which is freely available on GitHub and can be improved with third-party packages.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] It can be used to evaluate AI models in a range of areas including core knowledge, ability to reason, and autonomous capabilities.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] The regulation of artificial intelligence is the development of public sector policies and laws for promoting and regulating AI; it is therefore related to the broader regulation of algorithms.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] The regulatory and policy landscape for AI is an emerging issue in jurisdictions globally.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] According to AI Index at Stanford, the annual number of AI-related laws passed in the 127 survey countries jumped from one passed in 2016 to 37 passed in 2022 alone.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] Between 2016 and 2020, more than 30 countries adopted dedicated strategies for AI.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] Most EU member states had released national AI strategies, as had Canada, China, India, Japan, Mauritius, the Russian Federation, Saudi Arabia, United Arab Emirates, U.S., and Vietnam.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] Others were in the process of elaborating their own AI strategy, including Bangladesh, Malaysia and Tunisia.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] The Global Partnership on Artificial Intelligence was launched in June 2020, stating a need for AI to be developed in accordance with human rights and democratic values, to ensure public confidence and trust in the technology.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] Henry Kissinger, Eric Schmidt, and Daniel Huttenlocher published a joint statement in November 2021 calling for a government commission to regulate AI.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] In 2023, OpenAI leaders published recommendations for the governance of superintelligence, which they believe may happen in less than 10 years.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] In 2023, the United Nations also launched an advisory body to provide recommendations on AI governance; the body comprises technology company executives, government officials and academics.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] On 1 August 2024, the EU Artificial Intelligence Act entered into force, establishing the first comprehensive EU-wide AI regulation.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] In 2024, the Council of Europe created the first international legally binding treaty on AI, called the "Framework Convention on Artificial Intelligence and Human Rights, Democracy and the Rule of Law".
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] It was adopted by the European Union, the United States, the United Kingdom, and other signatories.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] In a 2022 Ipsos survey, attitudes towards AI varied greatly by country; 78% of Chinese citizens, but only 35% of Americans, agreed that "products and services using AI have more benefits than drawbacks".
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] A 2023 Reuters/Ipsos poll found that 61% of Americans agree, and 22% disagree, that AI poses risks to humanity.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] In a 2023 Fox News poll, 35% of Americans thought it "very important", and an additional 41% thought it "somewhat important", for the federal government to regulate AI, versus 13% responding "not very important" and 8% responding "not at all important".
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] In November 2023, the first global AI Safety Summit was held in Bletchley Park in the UK to discuss the near and far term risks of AI and the possibility of mandatory and voluntary regulatory frameworks.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] 28 countries including the United States, China, and the European Union issued a declaration at the start of the summit, calling for international co-operation to manage the challenges and risks of artificial intelligence.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] In May 2024 at the AI Seoul Summit, 16 global AI tech companies agreed to safety commitments on the development of AI.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] In March 2026, the United Nations convened the inaugural meeting of the Independent International Scientific Panel on AI, a 40-member expert body established under the Global Digital Compact to produce annual evidence-based reports on AI's societal impacts.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] The study of mechanical or "formal" reasoning began with philosophers and mathematicians in antiquity.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] The study of logic led directly to Alan Turing's theory of computation, which suggested that a machine, by shuffling symbols as simple as "0" and "1", could simulate any conceivable form of mathematical reasoning.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] This, along with concurrent discoveries in cybernetics, information theory and neurobiology, led researchers to consider the possibility of building an "electronic brain".
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] The field of AI research was founded at a workshop at Dartmouth College in 1956.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] The first AI program, Logic Theorist, was presented at the workshop, created by future Turing Award winner Allen Newell and future Nobel Laureate Herbert A.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] Many of the workshop attendees became the leaders of AI research in the 1960s.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] They and their students produced programs that the press described as "astonishing": computers were learning checkers strategies, solving word problems in algebra, proving logical theorems and speaking English.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] Artificial intelligence laboratories were set up at a number of British and U.S. universities in the latter 1950s and early 1960s.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] Researchers in the 1960s and the 1970s were convinced that their methods would eventually succeed in creating a machine with general intelligence and considered this the goal of their field.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] In 1965 Herbert Simon predicted, "machines will be capable, within twenty years, of doing any work a man can do".
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] In 1967 Marvin Minsky agreed, writing that "within a generation ... the problem of creating 'artificial intelligence' will substantially be solved".
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] They had, however, underestimated the difficulty of the problem.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] In 1974, both the U.S. and British governments cut off exploratory research in response to the criticism of Sir James Lighthill and ongoing pressure from the U.S.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] Congress to fund more productive projects.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] Minsky and Papert's book *Perceptrons* was understood as proving that artificial neural networks would never be useful for solving real-world tasks, thus discrediting the approach altogether.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] The "AI winter", a period when obtaining funding for AI projects was difficult, followed.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] In the early 1980s, AI research was revived by the commercial success of expert systems, a form of AI program that simulated the knowledge and analytical skills of human experts.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] By 1985, the market for AI had reached over a billion dollars.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] At the same time, Japan's fifth generation computer project inspired the U.S. and British governments to restore funding for academic research.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] However, beginning with the collapse of the Lisp Machine market in 1987, AI once again fell into disrepute, and a second, longer-lasting winter began.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] Up to this point, most of AI's funding had gone to projects that used high-level symbols to represent mental objects like plans, goals, beliefs, and known facts.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] In the 1980s, some researchers began to doubt that this approach would be able to imitate all the processes of human cognition, especially perception, robotics, learning and pattern recognition, and began to look into "sub-symbolic" approaches.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] Rodney Brooks rejected "representation" in general and focussed directly on engineering machines that move and survive.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] Judea Pearl, Lotfi Zadeh, and others developed methods that handled incomplete and uncertain information by making reasonable guesses rather than precise logic.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] But the most important development was the revival of "connectionism", including neural network research, by Geoffrey Hinton and others.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] In 1990, Yann LeCun successfully showed that convolutional neural networks can recognize handwritten digits, the first of many successful applications of neural networks.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] AI gradually restored its reputation in the late 1990s and early 21st century by exploiting formal mathematical methods and by finding specific solutions to specific problems.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] This "narrow" and "formal" focus allowed researchers to produce verifiable results and collaborate with other fields (such as statistics, economics and mathematics).
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] By 2000, solutions developed by AI researchers were being widely used, although in the 1990s they were rarely described as "artificial intelligence" (a tendency known as the AI effect).
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] However, several academic researchers became concerned that AI was no longer pursuing its original goal of creating versatile, fully intelligent machines.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] Beginning around 2002, they founded the subfield of artificial general intelligence (or "AGI"), which had several well-funded institutions by the 2010s.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] Deep learning began to dominate industry benchmarks in 2012 and was adopted throughout the field.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] For many specific tasks, other methods were abandoned.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] Deep learning's success was based on both hardware improvements (faster computers, graphics processing units, cloud computing) and access to large amounts of data (including curated datasets, such as ImageNet).
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] Deep learning's success led to an enormous increase in interest and funding in AI.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] The amount of machine learning research (measured by total publications) increased by 50% in the years 2015–2019.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] In 2016, issues of fairness and the misuse of technology were catapulted into center stage at machine learning conferences, publications vastly increased, funding became available, and many researchers re-focussed their careers on these issues.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] The alignment problem became a serious field of academic study.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] In the late 2010s and early 2020s, AGI companies began to deliver programs that created enormous interest.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] In 2015, AlphaGo, developed by DeepMind, beat the world champion Go player.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] The program taught only the game's rules and developed a strategy by itself.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] GPT-3 is a large language model that was released in 2020 by OpenAI and is capable of generating high-quality human-like text.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] ChatGPT, launched on 30 November 2022, became the fastest-growing consumer software application in history, gaining over 100 million users in two months.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] It marked what is widely regarded as AI's breakout year, bringing it into the public consciousness.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] These programs, and others, inspired an aggressive AI boom, where large companies began investing billions of dollars in AI research.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] According to AI Impacts, about US$50 billion annually was invested in "AI" around 2022 in the U.S. alone and about 20% of the new U.S. computer science PhD graduates have specialized in "AI".
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] About 800,000 "AI"-related U.S. job openings existed in 2022.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p02] According to PitchBook research, 22% of newly funded startups in 2024 claimed to be AI companies.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p03] Philosophical debates have historically sought to determine the nature of intelligence and how to make intelligent machines.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p03] Another major focus has been whether machines can be conscious, and the associated ethical implications.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p03] Many other topics in philosophy are relevant to AI, such as epistemology and free will.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p03] Rapid advancements have intensified public discussions on the philosophy and ethics of AI.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p03] Alan Turing investigated whether machines can show intelligent behaviour and think.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p03] In 1950, he proposed the Turing test, which measures the ability of a machine to simulate human conversation.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p03] Since we can only observe the behavior of the machine, it does not matter if it is "actually" thinking or literally has a "mind".
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p03] Russell and Norvig agree with Turing that intelligence must be defined in terms of external behavior, not internal structure.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p03] However, they are critical that the test requires the machine to imitate humans.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p03] McCarthy defines intelligence as "the computational part of the ability to achieve goals in the world".
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p03] Another AI founder, Marvin Minsky, similarly describes it as "the ability to solve hard problems".
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p03] *Artificial Intelligence: A Modern Approach* defines it as the study of agents that perceive their environment and take actions that maximize their chances of achieving defined goals.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p03] The many differing definitions of AI have been critically analyzed.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p03] During the 2020s AI boom, the term has been used as a marketing buzzword to promote products and services which do not use AI.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p03] The International Organization for Standardization describes an AI system as a "an engineered system that generates outputs such as content, forecasts, recommendations, or decisions for a given set of human‑defined objectives, and can operate with varying levels of automation".
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p03] AI systems are designed to operate with varying levels of autonomy".
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p03] No established unifying theory or paradigm has guided AI research for most of its history.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p03] The unprecedented success of statistical machine learning in the 2010s eclipsed all other approaches (so much so that some sources, especially in the business world, use the term "artificial intelligence" to mean "machine learning with neural networks").
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p03] This approach is mostly sub-symbolic, soft and narrow.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p03] Symbolic AI (or "GOFAI") simulated the high-level conscious reasoning that people use when they solve puzzles, express legal reasoning and do mathematics.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p03] It was highly successful at some "intelligent" tasks such as algebra or IQ tests.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p03] However, the symbolic approach failed on many tasks that humans solve easily, such as learning, recognizing an object or commonsense reasoning.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p03] Moravec's paradox is the discovery that high-level "intelligent" tasks were easy for AI, but low level "instinctive" tasks were extremely difficult.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p03] Philosopher Hubert Dreyfus had argued since the 1960s that human expertise depends on unconscious instinct rather than conscious symbol manipulation, and on having a "feel" for the situation, rather than explicit symbolic knowledge.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p03] Although his arguments had been ridiculed and ignored when they were first presented, eventually, AI research came to agree with him.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p03] The issue is not resolved: sub-symbolic reasoning can make many of the same inscrutable mistakes that human intuition does, such as algorithmic bias.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p03] The emerging field of neuro-symbolic artificial intelligence attempts to bridge the two approaches.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p03] "Neats" hope that intelligent behavior is described using simple, elegant principles (such as logic, optimization, or neural networks).
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p03] "Scruffies" expect that it necessarily requires solving a large number of unrelated problems.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p03] Neats defend their programs with theoretical rigor, scruffies rely mainly on incremental testing to see if they work.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p03] This issue was actively discussed in the 1970s and 1980s, but eventually was seen as irrelevant.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p03] Finding a provably correct or optimal solution is intractable for many important problems.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p03] Soft computing is a set of techniques, including genetic algorithms, fuzzy logic and neural networks, that are tolerant of imprecision, uncertainty, partial truth and approximation.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p03] Soft computing was introduced in the late 1980s and most successful AI programs in the 21st century are examples of soft computing with neural networks.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p03] AI researchers are divided as to whether to pursue the goals of artificial general intelligence and superintelligence directly or to solve as many specific problems as possible (narrow AI) in hopes these solutions will lead indirectly to the field's long-term goals.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p03] General intelligence is difficult to define and difficult to measure, and modern AI has had more verifiable successes by focusing on specific problems with specific solutions.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p03] The sub-field of artificial general intelligence studies this area exclusively.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p03] There is no settled consensus in philosophy of mind on whether a machine can have a mind, consciousness and mental states in the same sense that human beings do.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p03] This issue considers the internal experiences of the machine, rather than its external behavior.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p03] Mainstream AI research considers this issue irrelevant because it does not affect the goals of the field: to build machines that can solve problems using intelligence.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p03] Russell and Norvig add that "[t]he additional project of making a machine conscious in exactly the way humans are is not one that we are equipped to take on." However, the question has become central to the philosophy of mind.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p03] It is also typically the central question at issue in artificial intelligence in fiction.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p03] David Chalmers identified two problems in understanding the mind, which he named the "hard" and "easy" problems of consciousness.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p03] The easy problem is understanding how the brain processes signals, makes plans and controls behavior.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p03] The hard problem is explaining how this *feels* or why it should feel like anything at all, assuming we are right in thinking that it truly does feel like something (Dennett's consciousness illusionism says this is an illusion).
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p03] While human information processing is easy to explain, human subjective experience is difficult to explain.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p03] For example, it is easy to imagine a color-blind person who has learned to identify which objects in their field of view are red, but it is not clear what would be required for the person to *know what red looks like*.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p03] Computationalism is the position in the philosophy of mind that the human mind is an information processing system and that thinking is a form of computing.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p03] Computationalism argues that the relationship between mind and body is similar or identical to the relationship between software and hardware and thus may be a solution to the mind–body problem.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p03] This philosophical position was inspired by the work of AI researchers and cognitive scientists in the 1960s and was originally proposed by philosophers Jerry Fodor and Hilary Putnam.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p03] It is difficult or impossible to reliably evaluate whether an advanced AI is sentient (has the ability to feel), and if so, to what degree.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p03] But if there is a significant chance that a given machine can feel and suffer, then it may be entitled to certain rights or welfare protection measures, similarly to animals.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p03] Sapience (a set of capacities related to high intelligence, such as discernment or self-awareness) may provide another moral basis for AI rights.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p03] Robot rights are also sometimes proposed as a practical way to integrate autonomous agents into society.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p03] In 2017, the European Union considered granting "electronic personhood" to some of the most capable AI systems.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p03] Similarly to the legal status of companies, it would have conferred rights but also responsibilities.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p03] Critics argued in 2018 that granting rights to AI systems would downplay the importance of human rights, and that legislation should focus on user needs rather than speculative futuristic scenarios.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p03] They also noted that robots lacked the autonomy to take part in society on their own.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p03] Progress in AI increased interest in the topic.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p03] Proponents of AI welfare and rights often argue that AI sentience, if it emerges, would be particularly easy to deny.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p03] They warn that this may be a moral blind spot analogous to slavery or factory farming, which could lead to large-scale suffering if sentient AI is created and carelessly exploited.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p03] A superintelligence is a hypothetical agent that would possess intelligence far surpassing that of the brightest and most gifted human mind.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p03] If research into artificial general intelligence produced sufficiently intelligent software, it might be able to reprogram and improve itself.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p03] The improved software would be even better at improving itself, leading to what I.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p03] Good called an "intelligence explosion" and Vernor Vinge called a "singularity".
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p03] However, technologies cannot improve exponentially indefinitely, and typically follow an S-shaped curve, slowing when they reach the physical limits of what the technology can do.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p03] Robot designer Hans Moravec, cyberneticist Kevin Warwick and inventor Ray Kurzweil have predicted that humans and machines may merge in the future into cyborgs that are more capable and powerful than either.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p03] This idea, called transhumanism, has roots in the writings of Aldous Huxley and Robert Ettinger.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p03] Edward Fredkin argues that "artificial intelligence is the next step in evolution", an idea first proposed by Samuel Butler's "Darwin among the Machines" as far back as 1863, and expanded upon by George Dyson in his 1998 book *Darwin Among the Machines: The Evolution of Global Intelligence*.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p03] Thought-capable artificial beings have appeared as storytelling devices since antiquity, and have been a persistent theme in science fiction.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p03] A common trope in these works began with Mary Shelley's *Frankenstein*, where a human creation becomes a threat to its masters.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p03] Clarke's and Stanley Kubrick's *2001: A Space Odyssey* (both 1968), with HAL 9000, the murderous computer in charge of the *Discovery One* spaceship, as well as *Blade Runner* (1982), *The Terminator* (1984) and *The Matrix* (1999).
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p03] In contrast, the rare loyal robots such as Gort from *The Day the Earth Stood Still* (1951) and Bishop from *Aliens* (1986) are less prominent in popular culture.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p03] Isaac Asimov introduced the Three Laws of Robotics in many stories, most notably with the "Multivac" super-intelligent computer.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p03] Asimov's laws are often brought up during lay discussions of machine ethics; while almost all artificial intelligence researchers are familiar with Asimov's laws through popular culture, they generally consider the laws useless for many reasons, one of which is their ambiguity.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p03] Several works use AI to force us to confront the fundamental question of what makes us human, showing us artificial beings that have the ability to feel, and thus to suffer.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p03] This appears in Karel Čapek's *R.U.R.*, the films *A.I.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p03] Artificial Intelligence* and *Ex Machina*, as well as the novel *Do Androids Dream of Electric Sheep?*, by Philip K.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/artificial-intelligence-p03] Dick considers the idea that our understanding of human subjectivity is altered by technology created with artificial intelligence.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] There are two main types of EV chargers: alternating current (AC) charging stations and direct current (DC) charging stations.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] Electric vehicle batteries can only be charged by direct current electricity, while most mains electricity is delivered from the power grid as alternating current.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] For this reason, most electric vehicles have a built-in AC-to-DC converter commonly known as the "**onboard charger**" (**OBC**).
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] At an AC charging station, AC power from the grid is supplied to this onboard charger, which converts it into DC power to recharge the battery.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] DC chargers provide higher-power charging (which requires much larger AC-to-DC converters) by integrating the converter into the charging station, thereby avoiding size, weight, and cost constraints in vehicles.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] The station then directly supplies DC power to the vehicle, bypassing the onboard converter.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] Most modern electric vehicles can accept both AC and DC power.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] Public charging stations are typically found street-side or at retail shopping centers, government facilities, and other parking areas.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] Private charging stations are usually found at residences, workplaces, and hotels.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] Public charging accounted for approximately 46% of global EV charging infrastructure revenue in 2025, driven by high capital investment in DC fast charging networks, grid upgrades, and highway corridor expansion projects.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] Charging stations provide connectors that conform to a variety of international standards.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] DC charging stations are commonly equipped with multiple connectors to charge various vehicles that use competing standards.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] Multiple standards have been established for charging technology to enable interoperability across vendors.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] Standards are available for nomenclature, power, and connectors.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] Tesla developed proprietary technology in these areas and began building its charging network in 2012.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] The terms "electric vehicle connector" and "electric vehicle inlet" were previously defined in the same way under Article 625 of the United States National Electrical Code (NEC) of 1999.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] Tesla, Inc. uses the term *charging station* as the location of a group of chargers, and the term *connector* for an individual EVSE.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] Under the 1999 NEC, Level 1 charging equipment (as defined in the NEC handbook but not in the code) was connected to the grid through a standard NEMA 5-20R 3-prong electrical outlet with grounding, and a ground-fault circuit interrupter was required within 12 in (30 cm) of the plug.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] The supply circuit required protection at 125% of the maximum rated current; for example, charging equipment rated at 16 amperes ("amps" or "A") continuous current required a breaker sized to 20 A.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] Level 2 charging equipment (as defined in the handbook) was permanently wired and fastened at a fixed location under NEC-1999.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] It also required grounding and ground-fault protection; in addition, it required an interlock to prevent vehicle startup during charging and a safety breakaway for the cable and connector.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] A 40 A breaker (125% of continuous maximum supply current) was required to protect the branch circuit.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] For convenience and speedier charging, many early EVs preferred that owners and operators install Level 2 charging equipment, which was connected to the EV either through an inductive paddle (Magne Charge) or a conductive connector (Avcon).
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] Level 3 charging equipment used an off-vehicle rectifier to convert the input AC power to DC, which was then supplied to the vehicle.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] At the time it was written, the 1999 NEC handbook anticipated that Level 3 charging equipment would require utilities to upgrade their distribution systems and transformers.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] The Society of Automotive Engineers (SAE International) defines the general physical, electrical, communication, and performance requirements for EV charging systems used in North America, as part of standard SAE J1772, initially developed in 2001.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] SAE J1772 defines four levels of charging, two levels each for AC and DC supplies; the differences between levels are based upon the power distribution type, standards and maximum power.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] AC charging stations connect the vehicle's onboard charging circuitry directly to the AC supply.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] Commonly, though incorrectly, called "Level 3" charging based on the older NEC-1999 definition, DC charging is categorized separately in the SAE standard.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] In DC fast-charging, grid AC power is passed through an AC-to-DC converter in the station before reaching the vehicle's battery, bypassing any AC-to-DC converter on board the vehicle.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] Additional standards released by SAE for charging include SAE J3068 (three-phase AC charging, using the Type 2 connector defined in IEC 62196-2) and SAE J3105 (automated connection of DC charging devices).
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] In 2003, the International Electrotechnical Commission (IEC) adopted a majority of the SAE J1772 standard under IEC 62196-1 for international implementation.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] The North American Charging Standard (NACS) was developed by Tesla, Inc. for use in the company's vehicles.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] It remained a proprietary standard until 2022 when its specifications were published by Tesla.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] The connector is physically smaller than the J1772/CCS connector, and uses the same pins for both AC and DC charging functionality.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] As of November 2023, automakers Ford, General Motors, Rivian, Volvo, Polestar, Mercedes-Benz, Nissan, Honda, Jaguar, Fisker, Hyundai, BMW, Toyota, Subaru, and Lucid Motors have all committed to equipping their North American vehicles with NACS connectors in the future.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] Automotive startup Aptera Motors has also adopted the connector standard in its vehicles.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] Other automakers, such as Stellantis and Volkswagen had not made an announcement as of late 2023.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] To meet European Union (EU) requirements on recharging points, Tesla vehicles sold in the EU are equipped with a CCS Combo 2 port.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] Both the North America and the EU port take 480 V DC fast charging through Tesla's network of Superchargers, which variously use NACS and CCS charging connectors.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] Depending on the Supercharger version, power is supplied at 72, 150, or 250 kW, the first corresponding to DC Level 1 and the second and third corresponding to DC Level 2 of SAE J1772.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] As of Q4 2021, Tesla reported 3,476 supercharging locations worldwide and 31,498 supercharging chargers (about 9 chargers per location on average).
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] An extension to the CCS DC fast-charging standard for electric cars and light trucks was being developed as of 2020, which was slated to provide higher power charging for large commercial vehicles (Class 8, and possibly 6 and 7 as well, including school and transit buses).
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] When the Charging Interface Initiative e.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] (CharIN) task force was formed in March 2018, the new standard being developed was originally called High Power Charging (HPC) for Commercial Vehicles (HPCCV), later renamed Megawatt Charging System (MCS).
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] MCS is expected to operate in the range of 200–1500 V and 0–3000 A for a theoretical maximum power of 4.5 megawatts (MW).
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] The proposal calls for MCS charge ports to be compatible with existing CCS and HPC chargers.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] The task force released aggregated requirements in February 2019, which called for maximum limits of 1000 V DC (optionally, 1500 V DC) and 3000 A continuous rating.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] A connector design was selected in May 2019 and tested at the US National Renewable Energy Laboratory (NREL) in September 2020.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] Thirteen manufacturers participated in the test, which checked the coupling and thermal performance of seven vehicle inlets and eleven charger connectors.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] The final connector requirements and specification was adopted in December 2021 as MCS connector version 3.2.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] With support from Portland General Electric, on 21 April 2021 Daimler Trucks North America opened the "Electric Island", the first heavy-duty vehicle charging station, across the street from its headquarters in Portland, Oregon.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] The station is capable of charging eight vehicles simultaneously, and the charging bays are sized to accommodate tractor-trailers.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] In addition, the design is capable of accommodating >1 MW chargers once they are available.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] A startup company, WattEV, announced plans in May 2021 to build a 40-stall truck stop/charging station in Bakersfield, California.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] At full capacity, it was slated to provide a combined 25 MW of charging power, partially drawn from an on-site solar array and battery storage.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] Common connectors include Type 1 (Yazaki), Type 2 (Mennekes), CCS Combo 1 and 2, CHAdeMO, and Tesla.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] In India, "low-power" vehicles with traction battery voltages less than 100 V DC use the Bharat EV Charger standards.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] For AC charging (230 V, 15 A / 10 kW maximum), the Bharat EV Charger AC-001 standard endorses the IEC 60309 three-pin connector.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] For DC charging (48–72+ V, 200 A / 15 kW maximum), the corresponding Bharat EV Charger DC-001 standard endorses the same connector used in China (GB/T 20234.3).
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] For high-power vehicles, India has largely adopted global standards: IEC 62196 Type 2 connector for AC charging (≥22 kW) and CHAdeMO and CCS Combo 2 for DC charging (≥50 kW).
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] Although GB/T 20234.2 is physically capable of supporting three-phase power, the standard does not include its use; as such, the implementation is limited to single-phase.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] CCS DC charging requires power-line communication (PLC).
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] Two connectors are added at the bottom of Type 1 or Type 2 vehicle inlets and charging plugs to supply DC current.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] These are commonly known as Combo 1 or Combo 2 connectors.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] The choice of style inlets is normally standardized on a per-country basis so that public chargers do not need to fit cables with both variants.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] Generally, North America uses Combo 1 style vehicle inlets, while most of the rest of the world uses Combo 2.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] The CHAdeMO standard is favored by Nissan, Mitsubishi, and Toyota, while the SAE J1772 Combo standard is backed by GM, Ford, Volkswagen, BMW, and Hyundai.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] Both systems charge to 80% in approximately 20 minutes, but the two systems are incompatible.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] In the United States, many of the EVs first marketed in the late 1990s and early 2000s such as the GM EV1, Ford Ranger EV, and Chevrolet S-10 EV preferred the use of Level 2 (single-phase AC) EVSE, as defined under NEC-1999, to maintain acceptable charging speed.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] These EVSEs were fitted with either an inductive connector (Magne Charge) or a conductive connector (generally AVCON).
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] Proponents of the inductive system were GM, Nissan, and Toyota; DaimlerChrysler, Ford, and Honda backed the conductive system.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] Magne Charge paddles were available in two different sizes: an older, larger paddle (used for the EV1 and S-10 EV) and a newer, smaller paddle (used for the first-generation Toyota RAV4 EV, but backwards compatible with large-paddle vehicles through an adapter).
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] The larger paddle (introduced in 1994) was required to accommodate a liquid-cooled vehicle inlet charge port; the smaller paddle (introduced in 2000) interfaced with an air-cooled inlet instead.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] SAE J1773, which described the technical requirements for inductive paddle coupling, was first issued in January 1995, with another revision issued in November 1999.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] The influential California Air Resources Board adopted the conductive connector as its standard on 28 June 2001, based on lower costs and durability, and the Magne Charge paddle was discontinued by the following March.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] Three conductive connectors existed at the time, named according to their manufacturers: Avcon (aka butt-and-pin, used by Ford, Solectria, and Honda); Yazaki (aka pin-and-sleeve, on the RAV4 EV); and ODU (used by DaimlerChrysler).
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] IWC recommended the Avcon butt connector for North America, based on environmental and durability testing.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] As implemented, the Avcon connector used four contacts for Level 2 (L1, L2, Pilot, Ground) and added five more (three for serial communications, and two for DC power) for Level 3 (L1, L2, Pilot, Com1, Com2, Ground, Clean Data ground, DC+, DC−).
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] By 2009, J1772 had instead adopted the round pin-and-sleeve (Yazaki) connector as its standard implementation, and the rectangular Avcon butt connector was rendered obsolete.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] Charging time depends on the battery's capacity, power density, and charging power.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] The larger the capacity, the more charge the battery can hold (analogous to the size of a fuel tank).
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] Higher power density allows the battery to accept more charge per unit time (the size of the tank opening).
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] Higher charging power supplies more energy per unit time (analogous to a pump's flow rate).
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] An important downside of charging at fast speeds is that it also adds stress to the mains electricity grid.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] The California Air Resources Board specified a target minimum range of 150 miles (240 km) to qualify as a zero-emission vehicle, and further specified that the vehicle should allow for fast-charging.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] The effective charging power can be lower than the maximum charging power due to limitations of the battery or battery management system, charging losses (which can be as high as 25%), and vary over time due to charging limits applied by a charge controller.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] In early 2025, two Chinese companies announced battery technology to enable electric vehicles to drive long distances on a five-minute charge.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] BYD developed a battery with a peak charging capacity of 1,000 kW (1 MW), compared to US chargers then having peak rates of 400 kW or less.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] China's grid infrastructure allows high-power charging hubs to be connected directly to the power grid—sometimes even to high-voltage lines—avoiding the delay of local utility upgrades in the US.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] The usable battery capacity of a first-generation electric vehicle, such as the original Nissan Leaf, was about 20 kilowatt-hours (kWh), giving it a range of about 100 mi (160 km).
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] Tesla was the first company to introduce longer-range vehicles, initially releasing their Model S with battery capacities of 40 kWh, 60 kWh and 85 kWh, with the latter lasting for about 480 km (300 mi).
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] As of 2022 plug-in hybrid vehicles typically had an electric range of 15 to 60 miles (24–97 km).
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] To charge from the AC power supplied by the electrical grid, EVs have a small AC-to-DC converter built into the vehicle.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] The charging cable supplies AC power directly from the grid, and the vehicle converts this power to DC internally and charges its battery.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] The built-in converters on most EVs typically support charging speeds up to 6–7 kW, sufficient for overnight charging.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] To facilitate rapid recharging of EVs, much higher power (50–100+ kW) is necessary.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] This requires a much larger AC-to-DC converter which is not practical to integrate into the vehicle.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] Instead, the AC-to-DC conversion is performed by the charging station, and DC power is supplied to the vehicle directly, bypassing the built-in converter.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] Charging stations are usually accessible to multiple electric vehicles and are equipped with current or connection sensing mechanisms to disconnect the power when the EV is not charging.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] Sensor wires react more quickly, have fewer parts to fail, and are possibly less expensive to design and implement.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] Current sensors however can use standard connectors and can allow suppliers to monitor or charge for the electricity actually consumed.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] Longer drives require a network of public charging stations.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] In addition, they are essential for vehicles that lack access to a home charging station, as is common in multi-family housing.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] Costs vary greatly by country, power supplier, and power source.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] Some services charge by the minute, while others charge by the amount of energy received (measured in kilowatt-hours).
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] In the United States, some states have banned the use of charging by kWh.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] Charging stations may not need much new infrastructure in developed countries, less than delivering a new fuel over a new network.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] The stations can leverage the existing ubiquitous electrical grid.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] Charging stations are offered by public authorities, commercial enterprises, and some major employers to address a range of barriers.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] Options include simple charging posts for roadside use, charging cabinets for covered parking places, and fully automated charging stations integrated with power distribution equipment.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] As of December 2012, around 50,000 non-residential charging points were deployed in the US, Europe, Japan and China.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] As of August 2014, some 3,869 CHAdeMO quick chargers were deployed, with 1,978 in Japan, 1,181 in Europe and 686 in the United States, and 24 in other countries.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] As of December 2021 the total number of public and private EV charging stations was over 57,000 in the United States and Canada combined.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] As of May 2023, there are over 3.9 million public EV charging points worldwide, with Europe having over 600,000, China leading with over 2.7 million.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] United States has over 138,100 charging outlets for plug-in electric vehicles (EVs).
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] In January 2023, S&P Global Mobility estimated that the US has about 126,500 Level 2 and 20,431 Level 3 charging stations, plus another 16,822 Tesla Superchargers and Tesla destination chargers.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] This follows the 17,000 public charging stations that existed in 2012, mostly built by the State Grid of China as a pilot program in major cities such as Beijing, Shanghai, Hangzhou, Shenzhen and Hefei.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] As of December 2012, Japan had 1,381 public DC fast-charging stations, the largest deployment of fast chargers in the world, but only around 300 AC chargers.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] As of September 2013, the largest public charging networks in Australia were in the capital cities of Perth and Melbourne, with around 30 stations (7 kW AC) established in both cities – smaller networks exist in other capital cities.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] By 2024, the public charging network in Perth had grown to over 209 chargers while nationally there are over 5000 chargers across Australia as of 2026.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] In India, public electric vehicle (EV) charging stations are commonly located street-side and at retail shopping centers, government facilities, and other parking areas.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] Private charging stations are typically found at residences, workplaces, and hotels.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] As of December 2013, Estonia was the only country that had completed the deployment of an EV charging network with nationwide coverage, with 165 fast chargers available along highways at a maximum distance of between 40–60 km (25–37 mi), and a higher density in urban areas.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] As of November 2012, about 15,000 charging stations had been installed in Europe.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] As of March 2013, Norway had 4,029 charging points and 127 DC fast-charging stations.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] As part of its commitment to environmental sustainability, the Dutch government initiated a plan to establish over 200 fast (DC) charging stations across the country by 2015.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] The rollout will be undertaken by ABB and Dutch startup Fastned, aiming to provide at least one station every 50 km (31 mi) for the Netherlands' 16 million residents.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] In addition to that, the E-laad foundation installed about 3000 public (slow) charge points since 2009.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] Compared to other markets, such as China, the European electric car market has developed slowly.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] This, together with the lack of charging stations, has reduced the number of electric models available in Europe.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] In 2018 and 2019 the European Investment Bank (EIB) signed several projects with companies like Allego, Greenway, BeCharge and Enel X.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] The EIB loans will support the deployment of the charging station infrastructure with a total of €200 million.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] The UK government declared that it will ban the selling of new petrol and diesel vehicles by 2035 for a complete shift towards electric charging vehicles.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] As of August 2018, 800,000 electric vehicles and 18,000 charging stations operated in the United States, up from 5,678 public charging stations and 16,256 public charging points in 2013.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] As of October 2023, in the US and Canada, there are 6,502 stations with CHAdeMO connectors, 7,480 stations with SAE CCS1 connectors, and 7,171 stations with Tesla North American Charging System (NACS) connectors, according to the US Department of Energy's Alternative Fuels Data Center.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] As of March 2026, there are 78,444 EV charging stations with 241,301 chargers across the United States.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] California has the highest number of all the states and also has the most EVs registered..
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] Shopping centers have 95% of all fast DC chargers making them appropriate for quick fueling while 90% at hotels are the slower level 2 units.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] Colder areas in northern US states and Canada have some public power receptacles, primarily for use by block heaters.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] Although their circuit breakers prevent large current draws for other uses, they can be used to recharge electric vehicles, albeit slowly.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] In public lots, some such outlets are turned on only when the temperature falls below −30 °C (−22 °F), thus limiting their use for charging EVs.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] In June 2022, United States President Biden announced a plan for a standardized nationwide network of 500,000 electric vehicle charging stations by 2030 that will be agnostic to EV brands, charging companies, or location, in the United States.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] The US will provide US$5 billion between 2022 and 2026 to states through the National Electric Vehicle Infrastructure (NEVI) Formula Program to build charging stations along major highways and corridors.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] One such proposed corridor called Greenlane plans to establish charging infrastructure between Los Angeles, California and Las Vegas, Nevada.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] In April 2025, the flagship charging station was operational in Colton, California, with further locations in Barstow and Baker, under development.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] In July 2023, automakers General Motors, BMW, Honda, Hyundai, Kia, Mercedes, and Stellantis announced they were building a North American network of fast-chargers.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] Toyota would later join, and the venture was named Ionna.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] As of late 2023, a limited number of Tesla Superchargers started to open to non-Tesla vehicles through the use of a built in CCS adapter for existing superchargers.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] Other charging networks available for all electric vehicles include Electrify America, EVgo, and ChargePoint.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] In October 2023, Electrify America announced 15 agreements with various automakers for their electric vehicles to use its network of chargers.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] In May 2025, Tesla announced plans to develop a public, 46-station Megacharger network to support deployments of the Tesla Semi at ACT Expo.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] South Africa has a small, but expanding network of charging stations, and a growing number of EVs and PHEVs on the road.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] There is no direct government infrastructure spending on EV charging, and SA therefore has a patchwork of private charging sites.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] Investment in infrastructure is increasing.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] There are already proof of concept high-capacity DC chargers installed at various sites across SA, including the three 400 kW chargers at Charge's N12 North West facility, the 200 kW station at the Mall of Africa in Midrand, and the 150 kW one at Canal Walk in Cape Town.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] The cost of installing a charging station is estimated to be between R500,0000 and R2 million.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] To reach profitability, SA will need around 100,000 EVs on the road.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] As of 2025, there are around 3,500 new EVs sold per year in South Africa.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] Sales are expected to grow steadily, as new models are introduced into the market.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] At the same time, the industry was estimated to already be worth R2.8 billion.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] There are plans to build around more charging stations over the next few years.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] Companies included in these developments are Eskom, BYD, the National Automobile Association of South Africa, and Cape Town-based Charge, with its solar-powered passenger vehicle and electric truck charging stations, as part of a R100 million investment from the Development Bank of Southern Africa).
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] In April 2017 YPF, the state-owned oil company of Argentina, reported that it will install 220 fast-load stations for electric vehicles in 110 of its service stations in the national territory.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] Electric car manufacturers, charging infrastructure providers, and regional governments have entered into agreements and ventures to promote and provide electric vehicle networks of public charging stations.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] The EV Plug Alliance is an association of 21 European manufacturers that proposed an IEC norm and a European standard for sockets and plugs.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] Members (Schneider Electric, Legrand, Scame, Nexans, etc.) claimed that the system was safer because they use shutters.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] Prior consensus was that the IEC 62196 and IEC 61851-1 standards have already established safety by making parts non-live when touchable.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] Over 80% of electric vehicle charging is done at home, usually in a garage.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] In North America, Level 1 charging is connected to a standard 120 volt outlet and provides less than 5 miles (8.0 km) of range per hour of charging.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] To address the need for faster charging, Level 2 charging stations have become more prevalent.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] These stations operate at 240 volts and can significantly increase the charging speed, delivering up to more than 30 miles (48 km) of range per hour.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] Level 2 chargers offer a more practical solution for EV owners, especially for those who have higher daily mileage requirements.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] Charging stations can be installed using two main methods: hardwired connections to the main electrical panel box or through a cord and plug connected to a 240-volt receptacle.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] A popular choice for the latter is the NEMA 14-50 receptacle.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] This type of outlet provides 240 volts and, when wired to a 50-ampere circuit, can support charging at 40 amperes according to North American electrical code.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] This translates to a power supply of up to 9.6 kilowatts, offering a faster and more efficient charging experience.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] A battery swapping (or switching) station allow vehicles to exchange a discharged battery pack for a charged one, eliminating the charge interval.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] Battery swapping is common in electric forklift applications.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] The concept of an exchangeable battery service was proposed as early as 1896.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] It was first offered between 1910 and 1924, by Hartford Electric Light Company, through the GeVeCo battery service, serving electric trucks.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] The vehicle owner purchased the vehicle, without a battery, from General Vehicle Company (GeVeCo), part-owned by General Electric.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] The power was purchased from Hartford Electric in the form of an exchangeable battery.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] Both vehicles and batteries were designed to facilitate a fast exchange.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] The owner paid a variable per-mile charge and a monthly service fee to cover truck maintenance and storage.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] These vehicles covered more than 6 million miles (9.7 million kilometres).
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] Beginning in 1917, a similar service operated in Chicago for owners of Milburn Light Electric cars.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] 91 years later, a rapid battery replacement system was implemented to service 50 electric buses at the 2008 Summer Olympics.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] Better Place, Tesla, and Mitsubishi Heavy Industries considered battery switch approaches.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] One complicating factor was that the approach requires vehicle design modifications.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] In 2012, Tesla started building a proprietary fast-charging Tesla Supercharger network.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] In 2013, Tesla announced it would also support battery pack swaps.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] A demonstration swapping station was built at Harris Ranch and operated for a short period of time.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] However customers vastly preferred using the Superchargers, so the swapping program was shut down.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] The Better Place network was the first modern attempt at the battery switching model.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] The Renault Fluence Z.E. was the first car enabled to adopt the approach and was offered in Israel and Denmark.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] Better Place launched its first battery-swapping station in Israel, in Kiryat Ekron, near Rehovot in March 2011.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] Better Place filed for bankruptcy in Israel in May 2013.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] In June 2013, Tesla announced its plan to offer battery swapping.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] Tesla showed that a battery swap with the Model S took just over 90 seconds.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] Elon Musk said the service would be offered at around US$60 to US$80 at June 2013 prices.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] The vehicle purchase included one battery pack.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] After a swap, the owner could later return and receive their battery pack fully charged.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] A second option would be to keep the swapped battery and receive/pay the difference in value between the original and the replacement.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] In 2015 the company abandoned the idea for lack of customer interest.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] By 2022, Chinese luxury carmaker Nio had built more than 900 battery swap stations across China and Europe, up from 131 in 2020.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] Unlike filling stations, which need to be located near roads that tank trucks can enter conveniently, charging stations can theoretically be placed anywhere with access to electric power and adequate parking.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] Private locations include residences, workplaces, and hotels.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] Residences are by far the most common charging location.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] Residential charging stations typically lack user authentication and separate metering, and may require a dedicated circuit.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] Many vehicles being charged at residences simply use a cable that plugs into a standard household electrical outlet.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] Public stations have been sited along highways, in shopping centers, hotels, government facilities and at workplaces.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] Some gas stations offer EV charging stations.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] Some charging stations have been criticized as inaccessible, hard to find, out of order, and slow, thus slowing EV adoption.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] Public charge stations may charge a fee or offer free service based on government or corporate promotions.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] Charge rates vary from residential rates for electricity to many times higher.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] The premium is usually for the convenience of faster charging.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] Vehicles can typically be charged without the owner present, allowing the owner to partake in other activities.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] Sites include malls, freeway rest areas, transit stations, and government offices.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] Typically, AC Type 1/Type 2 plugs are used.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] Wireless charging uses inductive charging mats that charge without a wired connection and can be embedded in parking stalls or even on roadways.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] Mobile charging involves another vehicle that brings the charge station to the electric vehicle; the power is supplied via a fuel generator (typically gasoline or diesel), or a large battery.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] An offshore electricity recharging system named Stillstrom, to be launched by Danish shipping firm Maersk Supply Service, will give ships access to renewable energy while at sea.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] Connecting ships to electricity generated by offshore wind farms, Stillstrom is designed to cut emissions from idling ships.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] A smart grid is a power grid that can adapt to changing conditions by limiting service or adjusting prices.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] Some charging stations can communicate with the grid and activate charging when conditions are optimal, such as when prices are relatively low.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] Some vehicles allow the operator to control recharging.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] Vehicle-to-grid scenarios allow the vehicle battery to supply the grid during periods of peak demand.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] This requires communication between the grid, charging station, and vehicle.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] SAE International is developing related standards.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] ISO and IEC are developing similar standards known as ISO/IEC 15118, which also provide protocols for automatic payment.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] Electric vehicles (EVs) can be powered by renewable energy sources like wind, solar, hydropower, geothermal, biogas, and some low-impact hydroelectric sources.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] Renewable energy sources are generally less expensive, cleaner, and more sustainable than non-renewable sources like coal, natural gas, and petroleum power.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] Charging stations are powered by whatever the power grid runs on, which might include oil, coal, and natural gas.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] However, many companies have been making advancements towards clean energy for their charging stations.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] As of November 2023, Electrify America has invested over $5 million to develop over 50 solar-powered electric vehicle (EV) charging stations in rural California, including areas like Fresno County.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] These resilient Level 2 (L2) stations aren't tied to the electrical grid, and they provide drivers in rural areas access to EV charging via renewable resources.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] Electrify America’s Solar Glow 1 project, a 75-megawatt solar power initiative in San Bernardino County, is expected to generate 225,000 megawatt-hours of clean electricity annually, enough to power over 20,000 homes.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] Tesla's Superchargers and Destination Chargers are mostly powered by solar energy.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] Tesla's Superchargers have solar canopies with solar panels that generate energy to offset electricity use.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] Some Destination Chargers have solar panels mounted on canopies or nearby rooftops to generate energy.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] As of 2023, Tesla's global network was 100% renewable, achieved through a combination of onsite resources and annual renewable matching.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] The E-Move Charging Station is equipped with eight monocrystalline solar panels, which can supply 1.76 kW of solar power.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] In 2012, Urban Green Energy introduced the world's first wind-powered electric vehicle charging station, the Sanya SkyPump.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] The design features a 4 kW vertical-axis wind turbine paired with a GE WattStation.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] In 2021, Nova Innovation introduced the world's first direct from tidal power EV charge station.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] Along a section of the Highway E20 in Sweden, which connects Stockholm, Gothenburg and Malmö, a plate has been placed under the asphalt that interfaces with electric cars, recharging an electromagnetic coil receiver.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] This allows greater vehicle autonomy and reduces the size of the battery compartment.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] The technology is planned to be implemented along 3,000 km of Swedish roads.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] Sweden's first electrified stretch of road, and the world's first permanent one, connects the Hallsberg and Örebro area.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/charging-station] The work is scheduled for completion by 2025.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/demand-response] Utilities may signal demand requests to their customers in a variety of ways, including simple off-peak metering, in which power is cheaper at certain times of the day, and smart metering, in which explicit requests or changes in price can be communicated to customers.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/demand-response] The customer may adjust power demand by postponing some tasks that require large amounts of electric power, or may decide to pay a higher price for their electricity.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/demand-response] Some customers may switch part of their consumption to alternate sources, such as on-site solar panels and batteries.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/demand-response] In many respects, demand response can be put simply as a technology-enabled economic rationing system for electric power supply.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/demand-response] In demand response, voluntary rationing is accomplished by price incentives—offering lower net unit pricing in exchange for reduced power consumption in peak periods.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/demand-response] The direct implication is that users of electric power capacity not reducing usage (load) during peak periods will pay "surge" unit prices, whether directly, or factored into general rates.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/demand-response] Involuntary rationing, if employed, would be accomplished via rolling blackouts during peak load periods.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/demand-response] Practically speaking, summer heat waves and winter deep freezes might be characterized by planned power outages for consumers and businesses if voluntary rationing via incentives fails to reduce load adequately to match total power supply.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/demand-response] In 2013, it was expected that demand response programs will be designed to decrease electricity consumption or shift it from on-peak to off-peak periods depending on consumers' preferences and lifestyles.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/demand-response] In 2016 demand response was defined as "a wide range of actions which can be taken at the customer side of the electricity meter in response to particular conditions within the electricity system such as peak period network congestion or high prices".
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/demand-response] In 2010, demand response was defined as a reduction in demand designed to reduce peak demand or avoid system emergencies.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/demand-response] It can be a more cost-effective alternative than adding generation capabilities to meet the peak and occasional demand spikes.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/demand-response] The underlying objective of DR is to actively engage customers in modifying their consumption in response to pricing signals.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/demand-response] The goal is to reflect supply expectations through consumer price signals or controls and enable dynamic changes in consumption relative to price.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/demand-response] In electricity grids, DR is similar to dynamic demand mechanisms to manage customer consumption of electricity in response to supply conditions, for example, having electricity customers reduce their consumption at critical times or in response to market prices.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/demand-response] The difference is that demand response mechanisms respond to explicit requests to shut off, whereas dynamic demand devices passively shut off when stress in the grid is sensed.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/demand-response] Demand response can involve actually curtailing power used or by starting on-site generation which may or may not be connected in parallel with the grid.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/demand-response] This is a quite different concept from energy efficiency, which means using less power to perform the same tasks, on a continuous basis or whenever that task is performed.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/demand-response] At the same time, demand response is a component of smart energy demand, which also includes energy efficiency, home and building energy management, distributed renewable resources, and electric vehicle charging.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/demand-response] Current demand response schemes are implemented with large and small commercial as well as residential customers, often through the use of dedicated control systems to shed loads in response to a request by a utility or market price conditions.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/demand-response] Services (lights, machines, air conditioning) are reduced according to a preplanned load prioritization scheme during the critical time frames.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/demand-response] An alternative to load shedding is on-site generation of electricity to supplement the power grid.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/demand-response] Under conditions of tight electricity supply, demand response can significantly decrease the peak price and, in general, electricity price volatility.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/demand-response] Demand response is generally used to refer to mechanisms used to encourage consumers to reduce demand, thereby reducing the peak demand for electricity.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/demand-response] Since electrical generation and transmission systems are generally sized to correspond to peak demand (plus margin for forecasting error and unforeseen events), lowering peak demand reduces overall plant and capital cost requirements.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/demand-response] Depending on the configuration of generation capacity, however, demand response may also be used to increase demand (load) at times of high production and low demand.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/demand-response] Some systems may thereby encourage energy storage to arbitrage between periods of low and high demand (or low and high prices).
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/demand-response] Bitcoin mining is an electricity intensive process to convert computer hardware infrastructure, software skills and electricity into electronic currency.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/demand-response] Bitcoin mining is used to increase the demand during surplus hours by consuming cheaper power.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/demand-response] There are three types of demand response - emergency demand response, economic demand response and ancillary services demand response.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/demand-response] Emergency demand response is employed to avoid involuntary service interruptions during times of supply scarcity.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/demand-response] Economic demand response is employed to allow electricity customers to curtail their consumption when the productivity or convenience of consuming that electricity is worth less to them than paying for the electricity.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/demand-response] Ancillary services demand response consists of a number of specialty services that are needed to ensure the secure operation of the transmission grid and which have traditionally been provided by generators.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/demand-response] In most electric power systems, some or all consumers pay a fixed price per unit of electricity independent of the cost of production at the time of consumption.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/demand-response] The consumer price may be established by the government or a regulator, and typically represents an average cost per unit of production over a given timeframe (for example, a year).
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/demand-response] Consumption therefore is not sensitive to the cost of production in the short term (e.g. on an hourly basis).
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/demand-response] A pure economist might extrapolate the concept to hypothesize that consumers served under these fixed-rate tariffs are endowed with theoretical "call options" on electricity, though in reality, like any other business, the customer is simply buying what is on offer at the agreed price.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/demand-response] A customer in a department store buying a $10 item at 9.00 am might notice 10 sales staff on the floor but only one occupied serving him or her, while at 3.00 pm the customer could buy the same $10 article and notice all 10 sales staff occupied.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/demand-response] In virtually all power systems electricity is produced by generators that are dispatched in merit order, i.e., generators with the lowest marginal cost (lowest variable cost of production) are used first, followed by the next cheapest, etc., until the instantaneous electricity demand is satisfied.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/demand-response] In most power systems the wholesale price of electricity will be equal to the marginal cost of the highest cost generator that is injecting energy, which will vary with the level of demand.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/demand-response] Thus the variation in pricing can be significant: for example, in Ontario between August and September 2006, wholesale prices (in Canadian Dollars) paid to producers ranged from a peak of $318 per MW·h to a minimum of - (negative) $3.10 per MW·h.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/demand-response] It is not unusual for the price to vary by a factor of two to five due to the daily demand cycle.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/demand-response] A negative price indicates that producers were being charged to provide electricity to the grid (and consumers paying real-time pricing may have actually received a rebate for consuming electricity during this period).
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/demand-response] This generally occurs at night when demand falls to a level where all generators are operating at their minimum output levels and some of them must be shut down.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/demand-response] The negative price is the inducement to bring about these shutdowns in a least-cost manner.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/demand-response] The latter study found that even small shifts in peak demand would have a large effect on savings to consumers and avoided costs for additional peak capacity: a 1% shift in peak demand would result in savings of 3.9%, billions of dollars at the system level.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/demand-response] An approximately 10% reduction in peak demand (achievable depending on the elasticity of demand) would result in systems savings of between $8 and $28 billion.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/demand-response] While the net benefits would be significantly less than the claimed $35 billion, they would still be quite substantial.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/demand-response] In Ontario, Canada, the Independent Electricity System Operator has noted that in 2006, peak demand exceeded 25,000 megawatts during only 32 system hours (less than 0.4% of the time), while maximum demand during the year was just over 27,000 megawatts.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/demand-response] The ability to "shave" peak demand based on reliable commitments would therefore allow the province to reduce built capacity by approximately 2,000 megawatts.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/demand-response] In an electricity grid, electricity consumption and production must balance at all times; any significant imbalance could cause grid instability or severe voltage fluctuations, and cause failures within the grid.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/demand-response] Total generation capacity is therefore sized to correspond to total peak demand with some margin of error and allowance for contingencies (such as plants being off-line during peak demand periods).
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/demand-response] Operators will generally plan to use the least expensive generating capacity (in terms of marginal cost) at any given period, and use additional capacity from more expensive plants as demand increases.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/demand-response] Demand response in most cases is targeted at reducing peak demand to reduce the risk of potential disturbances, avoid additional capital cost requirements for additional plants, and avoid use of more expensive or less efficient operating plants.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/demand-response] Consumers of electricity will also pay higher prices if generation capacity is used from a higher-cost source of power generation.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/demand-response] Demand response may also be used to increase demand during periods of high supply and low demand.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/demand-response] Some types of generating plant must be run at close to full capacity (such as nuclear), while other types may produce at negligible marginal cost (such as wind and solar).
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/demand-response] Since there is usually limited capacity to store energy, demand response may attempt to increase load during these periods to maintain grid stability.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/demand-response] For example, in the province of Ontario in September 2006, there was a short period of time when electricity prices were negative for certain users.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/demand-response] Energy storage such as pumped-storage hydroelectricity is a way to increase load during periods of low demand for use during later periods.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/demand-response] Use of demand response to increase load is less common, but may be necessary or efficient in systems where there are large amounts of generating capacity that cannot be easily cycled down.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/demand-response] Some grids may use pricing mechanisms that are not real-time, but easier to implement (users pay higher prices during the day and lower prices at night, for example) to provide some of the benefits of the demand response mechanism with less demanding technological requirements.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/demand-response] In the UK, Economy 7 and similar schemes that attempt to shift demand associated with electric heating to overnight off-peak periods have been in operation since the 1970s.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/demand-response] More recently, in 2006 Ontario began implementing a "smart meter" program that implements "time-of-use" (TOU) pricing, which tiers pricing according to on-peak, mid-peak and off-peak schedules.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/demand-response] During the winter, on-peak is defined as morning and early evening, mid-peak as midday to late afternoon, and off-peak as nighttime; during the summer, the on-peak and mid-peak periods are reversed, reflecting air conditioning as the driver of summer demand.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/demand-response] As of May 1, 2015, most Ontario electrical utilities have completed converting all customers to "smart meter" time-of-use billing with on-peak rates about 200% and mid-peak rates about 150% of the off-peak rate per kWh.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/demand-response] Australia has national standards for Demand Response (AS/NZS 4755 series), which has been implemented nationwide by electricity distributors for several decades, e.g. controlling storage water heaters, air conditioners and pool pumps.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/demand-response] In 2016, how to manage electrical energy storage (e.g., batteries) has been added into the series of standards.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/demand-response] Energy consumers need some incentive to respond to such a request from a demand response provider.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/demand-response] Demand response incentives can be formal or informal.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/demand-response] The utility might create a tariff-based incentive by passing along short-term increases in the price of electricity, or they might impose mandatory cutbacks during a heat wave for selected high-volume users, who are compensated for their participation.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/demand-response] Other users may receive a rebate or other incentive based on firm commitments to reduce power during periods of high demand, sometimes referred to as *negawatts* (the term was coined by Amory Lovins in 1985).
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/demand-response] For example, California introduced its own ELRP, where upon an emergency declaration enrolled customers get a credit for lowering their electricity use ($1 per kWh in 2021, $2 in 2022).
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/demand-response] Commercial and industrial power users might impose load shedding on themselves, without a request from the utility.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/demand-response] Some businesses generate their own power and wish to stay within their energy production capacity to avoid buying power from the grid.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/demand-response] Some utilities have commercial tariff structures that set a customer's power costs for the month based on the customer's moment of highest use, or peak demand.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/demand-response] This encourages users to flatten their demand for energy, known as energy demand management, which sometimes requires cutting back services temporarily.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/demand-response] Smart metering has been implemented in some jurisdictions to provide real-time pricing for all types of users, as opposed to fixed-rate pricing throughout the demand period.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/demand-response] In this application, users have a direct incentive to reduce their use at high-demand, high-price periods.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/demand-response] Many users may not be able to effectively reduce their demand at various times, or the peak prices may be lower than the level required to induce a change in demand during short time periods (users have low price sensitivity, or elasticity of demand is low).
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/demand-response] Automated control systems exist, which, although effective, may be too expensive to be feasible for some applications.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/demand-response] Smart grid applications improve the ability of electricity producers and consumers to communicate with one another and make decisions about how and when to produce and consume electrical power.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/demand-response] This emerging technology will allow customers to shift from an event-based demand response where the utility requests the shedding of load, towards a more 24/7-based demand response where the customer sees incentives for controlling load all the time.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/demand-response] Although this back-and-forth dialogue increases the opportunities for demand response, customers are still largely influenced by economic incentives and are reluctant to relinquish total control of their assets to utility companies.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/demand-response] One advantage of a smart grid application is time-based pricing.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/demand-response] Customers who traditionally pay a fixed rate for consumed energy (kWh) and requested peak load can set their threshold and adjust their usage to take advantage of fluctuating prices.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/demand-response] This may require the use of an energy management system to control appliances and equipment and can involve economies of scale.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/demand-response] Another advantage, mainly for large customers with generation, is being able to closely monitor, shift, and balance load in a way that allows the customer to save peak load and not only save on kWh and kW/month but be able to trade what they have saved in an energy market.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/demand-response] Again, this involves sophisticated energy management systems, incentives, and a viable trading market.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/demand-response] Smart grid applications increase the opportunities for demand response by providing real time data to producers and consumers, but the economic and environmental incentives remain the driving force behind the practice.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/demand-response] One of the most important means of demand response in the future smart grids is electric vehicles.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/demand-response] Aggregation of this new source of energy, which is also a new source of uncertainty in the electrical systems, is critical to preserving the stability and quality of smart grids, consequently, the electric vehicle parking lots can be considered a demand response aggregation entity.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/demand-response] The modern power grid is making a transition from the traditional vertically integrated utility structures to distributed systems as it begins to integrate higher penetrations of renewable energy generation.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/demand-response] These sources of energy are often diffusely distributed and intermittent by nature.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/demand-response] These features introduce problems in grid stability and efficiency which lead to limitations on the amount of these resources which can be effectively added to the grid.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/demand-response] In a traditional vertically integrated grid, energy is provided by utility generators which are able to respond to changes in demand.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/demand-response] Generation output by renewable resources is governed by environmental conditions and is generally not able to respond to changes in demand.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/demand-response] Responsive control over noncritical loads that are connected to the grid has been shown to be an effective strategy able to mitigate undesirable fluctuations introduced by these renewable resources.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/demand-response] In this way instead of the generation responding to changes in demand, the demand responds to changes in generation.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/demand-response] In order to implement demand response systems, coordination of large numbers of distributed resources through sensors, actuators, and communications protocols becomes necessary.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/demand-response] To be effective, the devices need to be economical, robust, and yet still effective at managing their tasks of control.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/demand-response] In addition, effective control requires a strong capability to coordinate large networks of devices, managing and optimizing these distributed systems from both an economic and a security standpoint.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/demand-response] In addition, the increased presence of variable renewable generation drives a greater need for authorities to procure more ancillary services for grid balance.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/demand-response] One of these services is contingency reserve, which is used to regulate the grid frequency in contingencies.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/demand-response] As the ratio of inverter-based generation compared to conventional generation increases, the mechanical inertia used to stabilize frequency decreases.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/demand-response] When coupled with the sensitivity of inverter-based generation to transient frequencies, the provision of ancillary services from other sources than generators becomes increasingly important.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/demand-response] Technologies are available, and more are under development, to automate the process of demand response.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/demand-response] Such technologies detect the need for load shedding, communicate the demand to participating users, automate load shedding, and verify compliance with demand-response programs.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/demand-response] GridWise and EnergyWeb are two major federal initiatives in the United States to develop these technologies.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/demand-response] Universities and private industry are also doing research and development in this arena.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/demand-response] Scalable and comprehensive software solutions for DR enable business and industry growth.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/demand-response] Some utilities are considering and testing automated systems connected to industrial, commercial and residential users that can reduce consumption at times of peak demand, essentially delaying draw marginally.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/demand-response] Although the amount of demand delayed may be small, the implications for the grid (including financial) may be substantial, since system stability planning often involves building capacity for extreme peak demand events, plus a margin of safety in reserve.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/demand-response] Such events may only occur a few times per year.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/demand-response] The process may involve turning down or off certain appliances or sinks (and, when demand is unexpectedly low, potentially increasing usage).
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/demand-response] For example, heating may be turned down or air conditioning or refrigeration may be turned up (turning up to a higher temperature uses less electricity), delaying slightly the draw until a peak in usage has passed.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/demand-response] Although this is an experimental program, at scale these solutions have the potential to reduce peak demand considerably.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/demand-response] The success of such programs depends on the development of appropriate technology, a suitable pricing system for electricity, and the cost of the underlying technology.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/demand-response] Bonneville Power experimented with direct-control technologies in Washington and Oregon residences, and found that the avoided transmission investment would justify the cost of the technology.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/demand-response] Other methods to implementing demand response approach the issue of subtly reducing duty cycles rather than implementing thermostat setbacks.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/demand-response] These can be implemented using customized building automation systems programming, or through swarm-logic methods coordinating multiple loads in a facility (e.g.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/demand-response] Similar approach can be implemented for managing air conditioning peak demand in summer peak regions.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/demand-response] Pre-cooling or maintaining slightly higher thermostat setting can help with the peak demand reduction.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/demand-response] In 2008 it was announced that electric refrigerators will be sold in the UK sensing dynamic demand which will delay or advance the cooling cycle based on monitoring grid frequency but they are not readily available as of 2018.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/demand-response] Industrial customers are also providing demand response.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/demand-response] For example, Alcoa's Warrick Operation is participating in MISO as a qualified demand response resource, and the Trimet Aluminium uses its smelter as a short-term nega-battery.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/demand-response] The selection of suitable industries for demand response provision is typically based on an assessment of the so-called value of lost load.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/demand-response] Some data centers are located far apart for redundancy and can migrate loads between them, while also performing demand response.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/demand-response] Shedding loads during peak demand is important because it reduces the need for new power plants.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/demand-response] To respond to high peak demand, utilities build very capital-intensive power plants and lines.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/demand-response] Peak demand happens just a few times a year, so those assets run at a mere fraction of their capacity.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/demand-response] Electric users pay for this idle capacity through the prices they pay for electricity.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/demand-response] According to the Demand Response Smart Grid Coalition, 10%–20% of electricity costs in the United States are due to peak demand during only 100 hours of the year.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/demand-response] DR is a way for utilities to reduce the need for large capital expenditures, and thus keep rates lower overall; however, there is an economic limit to such reductions because consumers lose the productive or convenience value of the electricity not consumed.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/demand-response] Thus, it is misleading to only look at the cost savings that demand response can produce without also considering what the consumer gives up in the process.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/demand-response] It is estimated that a 5% lowering of demand would have resulted in a 50% price reduction during the peak hours of the California electricity crisis in 2000–2001.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/demand-response] With consumers facing peak pricing and reducing their demand, the market should become more resilient to intentional withdrawal of offers from the supply side.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/demand-response] Residential and commercial electricity use often vary drastically during the day, and demand response attempts to reduce the variability based on pricing signals.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/demand-response] Electric systems and grids typically scale total potential production to meet projected peak demand (with sufficient spare capacity to deal with unanticipated events).
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/demand-response] By "smoothing" demand to reduce peaks, less investment in operational reserve will be required, and existing facilities will operate more frequently.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/demand-response] In addition, significant peaks may only occur rarely, such as two or three times per year, requiring significant capital investments to meet infrequent events.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/demand-response] The report estimates that in 2004 potential demand response capability equaled about 20,500 megawatts (MW), 3% of total U.S. peak demand, while actual delivered peak demand reduction was about 9,000 MW (1.3% of peak), leaving ample margin for improvement.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/demand-response] It is further estimated that load management capability has fallen by 32% since 1996.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/demand-response] Factors affecting this trend include fewer utilities offering load management services, declining enrollment in existing programs, the changing role and responsibility of utilities, and changing supply/demand balance.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/demand-response] To encourage the use and implementation of demand response in the United States, the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission (FERC) issued Order No.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/demand-response] 745 in March 2011, which requires a certain level of compensation for providers of economic demand response that participate in wholesale power markets.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/demand-response] The order is highly controversial and has been opposed by a number of energy economists, including Professor William W.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/demand-response] Hogan at Harvard University's Kennedy School.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/demand-response] Professor Hogan asserts that the order overcompensates providers of demand response, thereby encouraging the curtailment of electricity whose economic value exceeds the cost of producing it.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/demand-response] Professor Hogan further asserts that Order No.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/demand-response] 745 is anticompetitive and amounts to "...an application of regulatory authority to enforce a buyer's cartel." Several affected parties, including the State of California, have filed suit in federal court challenging the legality of Order 745.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/demand-response] A debate regarding the economic efficiency and fairness of Order 745 appeared in a series of articles published in The Electricity Journal.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/demand-response] Circuit Court of Appeals vacated Order 745 in its entirety.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/demand-response] Whether the Court of Appeals erred in holding that the rule issued by the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission is arbitrary and capricious.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/demand-response] On January 25, 2016, the United States Supreme Court in a 6-2 decision in *FERC v.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/demand-response] Electric Power Supply Ass'n* concluded that the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission acted within its authority to ensure "just and reasonable" rates in the wholesale energy market.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/demand-response] 2222 on September 17, 2020, enabling distributed energy resources to participate in regional wholesale electricity markets.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/demand-response] Market operators submitted initial compliance plans by early 2022.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/demand-response] As of December 2009 National Grid had 2369 MW contracted to provide demand response, known as STOR, the demand side provides 839 MW (35%) from 89 sites.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/demand-response] Of this 839 MW approximately 750 MW is back-up generation with the remaining being load reduction.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] There are two main motivations to improve energy efficiency.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] Firstly, one motivation is to achieve cost savings during the operation of the appliance or process.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] However, installing an energy-efficient technology comes with an upfront cost, the capital cost.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] The different types of costs can be analyzed and compared with a life-cycle assessment.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] Another motivation for energy efficiency is to reduce greenhouse gas emissions and hence work towards climate action.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] A focus on energy efficiency can also have a national security benefit because it can reduce the amount of energy that has to be imported from other countries.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] Energy efficiency and renewable energy go hand in hand for sustainable energy policies.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] They are high priority actions in the energy hierarchy.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] Energy productivity, which measures the output and quality of goods and services per unit of energy input, can come from either reducing the amount of energy required to produce something, or from increasing the quantity or quality of goods and services from the same amount of energy.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] From the point of view of an energy consumer, the main motivation of energy efficiency is often simply saving money by lowering the cost of purchasing energy.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] Additionally, from an energy policy point of view, there has been a long trend in a wider recognition of energy efficiency as the "first fuel", meaning the ability to replace or avoid the consumption of actual fuels.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] Moreover, it has long been recognized that energy efficiency brings other benefits additional to the reduction of energy consumption.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] Some estimates of the value of these other benefits, often called *multiple benefits*, *co-benefits*, *ancillary benefits* or *non-energy benefits*, have put their summed value even higher than that of the direct energy benefits.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] These multiple benefits of energy efficiency include things such as reduced greenhouse gas emissions, reduced air pollution and improved health, and improved energy security.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] Methods for calculating the monetary value of these multiple benefits have been developed, including e.g. the choice experiment method for improvements that have a subjective component (such as aesthetics or comfort) and Tuominen-Seppänen method for price risk reduction.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] When included in the analysis, the economic benefit of energy efficiency investments can be shown to be significantly higher than simply the value of the saved energy.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] Energy efficiency has proved to be a cost-effective strategy for building economies without necessarily increasing energy consumption.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] For example, the state of California began implementing energy-efficiency measures in the mid-1970s, including building code and appliance standards with strict efficiency requirements.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] During the following years, California's energy consumption has remained approximately flat on a per capita basis while national US consumption doubled.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] As part of its strategy, California implemented a "loading order" for new energy resources that puts energy efficiency first, renewable electricity supplies second, and new fossil-fired power plants last.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] States such as Connecticut and New York have created quasi-public Green Banks to help residential and commercial building-owners finance energy efficiency upgrades that reduce emissions and cut consumers' energy costs.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] Energy conservation is broader than energy efficiency in including active efforts to decrease energy consumption, for example through behaviour change, in addition to using energy more efficiently.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] Examples of conservation without efficiency improvements are heating a room less in winter, using the car less, air-drying your clothes instead of using the dryer, or enabling energy saving modes on a computer.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] As with other definitions, the boundary between efficient energy use and energy conservation can be fuzzy, but both are important in environmental and economic terms.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] Energy efficiency—using less energy to deliver the same goods or services, or delivering comparable services with less goods—is a cornerstone of many sustainable energy strategies.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] The International Energy Agency (IEA) has estimated that increasing energy efficiency could achieve 40% of greenhouse gas emission reductions needed to fulfil the Paris Agreement's goals.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] Energy can be conserved by increasing the technical efficiency of appliances, vehicles, industrial processes, and buildings.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] If the demand for energy services remains constant, improving energy efficiency will reduce energy consumption and carbon emissions.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] However, many efficiency improvements do not reduce energy consumption by the amount predicted by simple engineering models.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] This is because they make energy services cheaper, and so consumption of those services increases.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] For example, since fuel efficient vehicles make travel cheaper, consumers may choose to drive farther, thereby offsetting some of the potential energy savings.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] Similarly, an extensive historical analysis of technological efficiency improvements has conclusively shown that energy efficiency improvements were almost always outpaced by economic growth, resulting in a net increase in resource use and associated pollution.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] These are examples of the direct rebound effect.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] Estimates of the size of the rebound effect range from roughly 5% to 40%.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] The rebound effect is likely to be less than 30% at the household level and may be closer to 10% for transport.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] A rebound effect of 30% implies that improvements in energy efficiency should achieve 70% of the reduction in energy consumption projected using engineering models.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] Modern appliances, such as, freezers, ovens, stoves, dishwashers, clothes washers and dryers, use significantly less energy than older appliances.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] Current energy-efficient refrigerators, for example, use 40 percent less energy than conventional models did in 2001.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] Following this, if all households in Europe changed their more than ten-year-old appliances into new ones, 20 billion kWh of electricity would be saved annually, hence reducing CO2 emissions by almost 18 billion kg.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] In the US, the corresponding figures would be 17 billion kWh of electricity and 27,000,000,000 lb (1.2×1010 kg) CO2.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] According to a 2009 study from McKinsey & Company the replacement of old appliances is one of the most efficient global measures to reduce emissions of greenhouse gases.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] Modern power management systems also reduce energy usage by idle appliances by turning them off or putting them into a low-energy mode after a certain time.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] Many countries identify energy-efficient appliances using energy input labeling.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] The impact of energy efficiency on peak demand depends on when the appliance is used.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] For example, an air conditioner uses more energy during the afternoon when it is hot.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] Therefore, an energy-efficient air conditioner will have a larger impact on peak demand than off-peak demand.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] An energy-efficient dishwasher, on the other hand, uses more energy during the late evening when people do their dishes.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] This appliance may have little to no impact on peak demand.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] Over the period 2001–2021, tech companies have replaced traditional silicon switches in an electric circuit with quicker gallium nitride transistors to make new gadgets as energy efficient as feasible.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] Gallium nitride transistors are, however, more costly.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] This is a significant change in lowering the carbon footprint.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] A building's location and surroundings play a key role in regulating its temperature and illumination.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] For example, trees, landscaping, and hills can provide shade and block wind.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] In cooler climates, designing northern hemisphere buildings with south facing windows and southern hemisphere buildings with north facing windows increases the amount of sun (ultimately heat energy) entering the building, minimizing energy use, by maximizing passive solar heating.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] Tight building design, including energy-efficient windows, well-sealed doors, and additional thermal insulation of walls, basement slabs, and foundations can reduce heat loss by 25 to 50 percent.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] Dark roofs may become up to 39 °C (70 °F) hotter than the most reflective white surfaces.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] They transmit some of this additional heat inside the building.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] US Studies have shown that lightly colored roofs use 40 percent less energy for cooling than buildings with darker roofs.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] White roof systems save more energy in sunnier climates.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] Advanced electronic heating and cooling systems can moderate energy consumption and improve the comfort of people in the building.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] Proper placement of windows and skylights as well as the use of architectural features that reflect light into a building can reduce the need for artificial lighting.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] Increased use of natural and task lighting has been shown by one study to increase productivity in schools and offices.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] Compact fluorescent lamps use two-thirds less energy and may last 6 to 10 times longer than incandescent light bulbs.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] Newer fluorescent lights produce a natural light, and in most applications they are cost effective, despite their higher initial cost, with payback periods as low as a few months.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] LED lamps use only about 10% of the energy an incandescent lamp requires.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] Leadership in Energy and Environmental Design (LEED) is a rating system organized by the US Green Building Council (USGBC) to promote environmental responsibility in building design.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] In 2013, USGBC developed the LEED Dynamic Plaque, a tool to track building performance against LEED metrics and a potential path to recertification.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] The following year, the council collaborated with Honeywell to pull data on energy and water use, as well as indoor air quality from a BAS to automatically update the plaque, providing a near-real-time view of performance.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] The USGBC office in Washington, D.C. is one of the first buildings to feature the live-updating LEED Dynamic Plaque.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] Industries use a large amount of energy to power a diverse range of manufacturing and resource extraction processes.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] Many industrial processes require large amounts of heat and mechanical power, most of which is delivered as natural gas, petroleum fuels, and electricity.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] In addition some industries generate fuel from waste products that can be used to provide additional energy.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] Because industrial processes are so diverse it is impossible to describe the multitude of possible opportunities for energy efficiency in industry.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] Many depend on the specific technologies and processes in use at each industrial facility.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] There are, however, a number of processes and energy services that are widely used in many industries.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] Various industries generate steam and electricity for subsequent use within their facilities.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] When electricity is generated, the heat that is produced as a by-product can be captured and used for process steam, heating or other industrial purposes.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] Conventional electricity generation is about 30% efficient, whereas combined heat and power (also called co-generation) converts up to 90 percent of the fuel into usable energy.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] Advanced boilers and furnaces can operate at higher temperatures while burning less fuel.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] These technologies are more efficient and produce fewer pollutants.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] Over 45 percent of the fuel used by US manufacturers is burnt to make steam.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] The typical industrial facility can reduce this energy usage 20 percent (according to the US Department of Energy) by insulating steam and condensate return lines, stopping steam leakage, and maintaining steam traps.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] Electric motors usually run at a constant speed, but a variable speed drive allows the motor's energy output to match the required load.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] This achieves energy savings ranging from 3 to 60 percent, depending on how the motor is used.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] Motor coils made of superconducting materials can also reduce energy losses.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] Motors may also benefit from voltage optimization.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] Industry uses a large number of pumps and compressors of all shapes and sizes and in a wide variety of applications.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] The efficiency of pumps and compressors depends on many factors but often improvements can be made by implementing better process control and better maintenance practices.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] Compressors are commonly used to provide compressed air which is used for sand blasting, painting, and other power tools.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] According to the US Department of Energy, optimizing compressed air systems by installing variable speed drives, along with preventive maintenance to detect and fix air leaks, can improve energy efficiency 20 to 50 percent.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] The estimated energy efficiency for an automobile is 280 Passenger-Mile/106 Btu.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] There are several ways to enhance a vehicle's energy efficiency.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] Using improved aerodynamics to minimize drag can increase vehicle fuel efficiency.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] Reducing vehicle weight can also improve fuel economy, which is why composite materials are widely used in car bodies.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] More advanced tires, with decreased tire to road friction and rolling resistance, can save gasoline.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] Fuel economy can be improved by up to 3.3% by keeping tires inflated to the correct pressure.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] Replacing a clogged air filter can improve a cars fuel consumption by as much as 10 percent on older vehicles.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] On newer vehicles (1980s and up) with fuel-injected, computer-controlled engines, a clogged air filter has no effect on mpg but replacing it may improve acceleration by 6-11 percent.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] Aerodynamics also aid in efficiency of a vehicle.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] The design of a car impacts the amount of gas needed to move it through air.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] Aerodynamics involves the air around the car, which can affect the efficiency of the energy expended.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] Turbochargers can increase fuel efficiency by allowing a smaller displacement engine.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] The 'Engine of the year 2011' is the Fiat TwinAir engine equipped with an MHI turbocharger.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] "Compared with a 1.2-liter 8v engine, the new 85 HP turbo has 23% more power and a 30% better performance index.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] Energy-efficient vehicles may reach twice the fuel efficiency of the average automobile.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] Cutting-edge designs, such as the diesel Mercedes-Benz Bionic concept vehicle have achieved a fuel efficiency as high as 84 miles per US gallon (2.8 L/100 km; 101 mpg‑imp), four times the current conventional automotive average.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] The mainstream trend in automotive efficiency is the rise of electric vehicles (all-electric or hybrid electric).
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] Electric engines have more than double the efficiency of internal combustion engines.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] Hybrids, like the Toyota Prius, use regenerative braking to recapture energy that would dissipate in normal cars; the effect is especially pronounced in city driving.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] Plug-in hybrids also have increased battery capacity, which makes it possible to drive for limited distances without burning any gasoline; in this case, energy efficiency is dictated by whatever process (such as coal-burning, hydroelectric, or renewable source) created the power.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] Plug-ins can typically drive for around 40 miles (64 km) purely on electricity without recharging; if the battery runs low, a gas engine kicks in allowing for extended range.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] Finally, all-electric cars are also growing in popularity.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] Cities around the globe light up millions of streets with 300 million lights.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] Some cities are seeking to reduce street light power consumption by dimming lights during off-peak hours or switching to LED lamps.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] LED lamps are known to reduce the energy consumption by 50% to 80%.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] There are several ways to improve aviation's use of energy through modifications aircraft and air traffic management.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] Aircraft improve with better aerodynamics, engines and weight.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] Seat density and cargo load factors contribute to efficiency.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] Air traffic management systems can allow automation of takeoff, landing, and collision avoidance, as well as within airports, from simple things like HVAC and lighting to more complex tasks such as security and scanning.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] At the 2023 United Nations Climate Change Conference, one of the adopted declaration was the GLOBAL RENEWABLES AND ENERGY EFFICIENCY PLEDGE signed by 123 countries.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] The declaration includes obligations to consider energy efficiency as "first fuel" and double the rate of increase in energy efficiency from 2% per year to 4% per year by the year 2030.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] China and India did not sign this pledge.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] International standards ISO 17743 and ISO 17742 provide a documented methodology for calculating and reporting on energy savings and energy efficiency for countries and cities.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] The first EU-wide energy efficiency target was set in 1998.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] Member states agreed to improve energy efficiency by 1 percent a year over twelve years.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] In addition, legislation about products, industry, transport and buildings has contributed to a general energy efficiency framework.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] More effort is needed to address heating and cooling: there is more heat wasted during electricity production in Europe than is required to heat all buildings in the continent.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] All in all, EU energy efficiency legislation is estimated to deliver savings worth the equivalent of up to 326 million tons of oil per year by 2020.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] The EU set itself a 20% energy savings target by 2020 compared to 1990 levels, but member states decide individually how energy savings will be achieved.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] At an EU summit in October 2014, EU countries agreed on a new energy efficiency target of 27% or greater by 2030.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] One mechanism used to achieve the target of 27% is the 'Suppliers Obligations & White Certificates'.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] The ongoing debate around the 2016 Clean Energy Package also puts an emphasis on energy efficiency, but the goal will probably remain around 30% greater efficiency compared to 1990 levels.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] Some have argued that this will not be enough for the EU to meet its Paris Agreement goals of reducing greenhouse gas emissions by 40% compared to 1990 levels.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] In the European Union, 78% of enterprises proposed energy-saving methods in 2023, 67% listed energy contract renegotiation as a strategy, and 62% stated passing on costs to consumers as a plan to deal with energy market trends.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] Larger organisations were found more likely to invest in energy efficiency, green innovation, and climate change, with a significant rise in energy efficiency investments reported by SMEs and mid-cap companies.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] Energy efficiency is central to energy policy in Germany.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] Progress toward improved efficiency has been steady.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] Some however believe energy efficiency is still under-recognized in terms of its contribution to Germany's energy transformation (or *Energiewende*).
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] Efforts to reduce final energy consumption in transport sector have not been successful, with a growth of 1.7% between 2005 and 2014.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] This growth is due to both road passenger and road freight transport.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] Both sectors increased their overall distance travelled to record the highest figures ever for Germany.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] Rebound effects played a significant role, both between improved vehicle efficiency and the distance travelled, and between improved vehicle efficiency and an increase in vehicle weights and engine power.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] In 2014, the German federal government released its National Action Plan on Energy Efficiency (NAPE).
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] The areas covered are the energy efficiency of buildings, energy conservation for companies, consumer energy efficiency, and transport energy efficiency.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] In 2016, the German government released a green paper on energy efficiency for public consultation (in German).
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] It outlines the potential challenges and actions needed to reduce energy consumption in Germany over the coming decades.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] At the document's launch, economics and energy minister Sigmar Gabriel said "we do not need to produce, store, transmit and pay for the energy that we save".
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] The green paper prioritizes the efficient use of energy as the "first" response and also outlines opportunities for sector coupling, including using renewable power for heating and transport.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] Other proposals include a flexible energy tax which rises as petrol prices fall, thereby incentivizing fuel conservation despite low oil prices.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] In Spain, four out of every five buildings use more energy than they should.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] They are either inadequately insulated or consume energy inefficiently.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] The Unión de Créditos Immobiliarios (UCI), which has operations in Spain and Portugal, is increasing loans to homeowners and building management groups for energy-efficiency initiatives.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] Their Residential Energy Rehabilitation initiative aims to remodel and encourage the use of renewable energy in at least 3720 homes in Madrid, Barcelona, Valencia, and Seville.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] The works are expected to mobilize around €46.5 million in energy efficiency upgrades by 2025 and save approximately 8.1 GWh of energy.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] It has the ability to reduce carbon emissions by 7,545 tonnes per year.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] In May 2016 Poland adopted a new Act on Energy Efficiency, to enter into force on 1 October 2016.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] In July 2009, the Council of Australian Governments, which represents the individual states and territories of Australia, agreed to a National Strategy on Energy Efficiency (NSEE).
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] This is a ten-year plan accelerating the implementation of a nationwide adoption of energy-efficient practices and a preparation for the country's transformation into a low carbon future.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] The overriding agreement that governs this strategy is the National Partnership Agreement on Energy Efficiency.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] In August 2017, the Government of Canada released Build Smart - Canada's Buildings Strategy, as a key driver of the Pan-Canadian Framework on Clean Growth and Climate Change, Canada's national climate strategy.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] A 2011 Energy Modeling Forum study covering the United States examined how energy efficiency opportunities will shape future fuel and electricity demand over the next several decades.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] The US economy is already set to lower its energy and carbon intensity, but explicit policies will be necessary to meet climate goals.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/efficient-energy-use] These policies include: a carbon tax, mandated standards for more efficient appliances, buildings and vehicles, and subsidies or reductions in the upfront costs of new more energy-efficient equipment.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/energy-accounting] Energy accounting is a system used in energy management systems to measure and analyze energy consumption to improve energy efficiency within an organization.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/energy-accounting] Organisations such as Intel corporation use these systems to track energy usage.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/energy-accounting] Various energy transformations are possible.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/energy-accounting] An energy balance can be used to track energy through a system.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/energy-accounting] This becomes a useful tool for determining resource use and environmental impacts.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/energy-accounting] How much energy is needed at each point in a system is measured, as well as the form of that energy.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/energy-accounting] An accounting system keeps track of energy in, energy out, and non-useful energy versus work done, and transformations within a system.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/energy-accounting] Sometimes, non-useful work is what is often responsible for environmental problems.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/energy-accounting] Energy returned on energy invested (EROEI) is the ratio of energy delivered by an energy technology to the energy invested to set up the technology.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/energy-conservation-measure-p01] Green engineering practices improve the life cycle of the components of machines which convert energy from one form into another.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/energy-conservation-measure-p01] Observing appliance usage, establishing an energy usage profile, and revealing energy consumption patterns in circumstances where energy is used poorly, can pinpoint user habits and behaviors in energy consumption.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/energy-conservation-measure-p01] Appliance energy profiling helps identify inefficient appliances with high energy consumption and energy load.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/energy-conservation-measure-p01] Seasonal variations also greatly influence energy load, as more air-conditioning is used in warmer seasons and heating in colder seasons.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/energy-conservation-measure-p01] Achieving a balance between energy load and user comfort is complex yet essential for energy preservation.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/energy-conservation-measure-p01] On a large scale, a few factors affect energy consumption trends, including political issues, technological developments, economic growth, and environmental concerns.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/energy-conservation-measure-p01] User behavior has a significant effect on energy conservation.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/energy-conservation-measure-p01] It involves user activity detection, profiling, and appliance interaction behaviors.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/energy-conservation-measure-p01] User profiling consists of the identification of energy usage patterns of the user and replacing required system settings with automated settings that can be initiated on request.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/energy-conservation-measure-p01] Within user profiling, personal characteristics are instrumental in affecting energy conservation behavior.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/energy-conservation-measure-p01] These characteristics include household income, education, gender, age, and social norms.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/energy-conservation-measure-p01] User behavior also relies on the impact of personality traits, social norms, and attitudes on energy conservation behavior.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/energy-conservation-measure-p01] Beliefs and attitudes toward a convenient lifestyle, environmentally friendly transport, energy security, and residential location choices affect energy conservation behavior.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/energy-conservation-measure-p01] As a result, energy conservation can be made possible by adopting pro-environmental behavior and energy-efficient systems.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/energy-conservation-measure-p01] Education on approaches to energy conservation can result in wise energy use.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/energy-conservation-measure-p01] The choices made by the users yield energy usage patterns.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/energy-conservation-measure-p01] Rigorous analysis of these usage patterns identifies waste energy patterns, and improving those patterns may reduce significant energy load.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/energy-conservation-measure-p01] Therefore, human behavior is critical to determining the implications of energy conservation measures and solving environmental problems.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/energy-conservation-measure-p01] Substantial energy conservation may be achieved if users' habit loops are modified.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/energy-conservation-measure-p01] User habits significantly impact energy demand; thus, providing recommendations for improving user habits contributes to energy conservation.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/energy-conservation-measure-p01] Micro-moments are essential in realizing energy consumption patterns and are identified using a variety of sensing units positioned in prominent areas across the home.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/energy-conservation-measure-p01] The micro-moment is an event that changes the state of the appliance from inactive to active and helps in building users' energy consumption profiles according to their activities.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/energy-conservation-measure-p01] Energy conservation can be achieved through user habits by following energy-saving recommendations at micro-moments.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/energy-conservation-measure-p01] Unnecessary energy usage can be decreased by selecting a suitable schedule for appliance operation.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/energy-conservation-measure-p01] Creating an effective scheduling system requires an understanding of user habits regarding appliances.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/energy-conservation-measure-p01] Many techniques for energy conservation comprise off-peak scheduling, which means operating an appliance in a low-price energy hour.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/energy-conservation-measure-p01] This schedule can be achieved after user habits regarding appliance use are understood.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/energy-conservation-measure-p01] Most energy providers divide the energy tariff into high and low-price hours; therefore, scheduling an appliance to work an off-peak hour will significantly reduce electricity bills.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/energy-conservation-measure-p01] User activity detection leads to the precise detection of appliances required for an activity.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/energy-conservation-measure-p01] If an appliance is active but not required for a user's current activity, it wastes energy and can be turned off to conserve energy.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/energy-conservation-measure-p01] The precise identification of user activities is necessary to achieve this method of energy conservation.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/energy-conservation-measure-p01] Energy conservation measures have primarily focused on technological innovations to improve efficiencies and financial incentives with theoretical explanations obtained from the mentioned analytical traditions.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/energy-conservation-measure-p01] Existing buildings can improve energy efficiency by changing structural maintenance materials, adjusting the composition of air conditioning systems, selecting energy-saving equipment, and formulating subsidy policies.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/energy-conservation-measure-p01] These measures can improve users' thermal comfort and reduce buildings' environmental impact.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/energy-conservation-measure-p01] The selection of combinatorial optimization schemes that contain measures to guide and restrict users' behavior in addition to carrying out demand-side management can dynamically adjust energy consumption.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/energy-conservation-measure-p01] At the same time, economic means should enable users to change their behavior and achieve a low-carbon life.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/energy-conservation-measure-p01] Combination optimization and pricing incentives reduce building energy consumption and carbon emissions and reduce users' costs.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/energy-conservation-measure-p01] Monitoring through energy audits can help in achieving energy efficiency in existing buildings.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/energy-conservation-measure-p01] An energy audit is an inspection and analysis of energy use in a system intending to reduce energy input without negatively affecting output.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/energy-conservation-measure-p01] Energy audits can determine specific opportunities for energy conservation and efficiency measures as well as determine cost-effective strategies.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/energy-conservation-measure-p01] Training professionals typically accomplish this and can be part of some national programs discussed above.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/energy-conservation-measure-p01] Smartphone apps enables homeowners to complete relatively sophisticated energy audits themselves.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/energy-conservation-measure-p01] For instance, smart thermostats can connect to standard HVAC systems to maintain energy-saving indoor temperatures.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/energy-conservation-measure-p01] In addition, data loggers can also be installed to monitor the interior temperature and humidity levels to provide a more precise understanding of the conditions.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/energy-conservation-measure-p01] If the data gathered is compared with the users' perceptions of comfort, more fine-tuning of the interiors can be implemented (e.g., increasing the temperature where A.C. is used to prevent over-cooling).
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/energy-conservation-measure-p01] Building technologies and smart meters can allow commercial and residential energy users to visualize the impact their energy use can have in their workplaces or homes.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/energy-conservation-measure-p01] Advanced real-time energy metering can help people save energy through their actions.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/energy-conservation-measure-p01] Another approach towards energy conservation is the implementation of ECMs in commercial buildings, which often employ Energy Service Companies (ESCOs) experienced in energy performance contracting.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/energy-conservation-measure-p01] This industry has been around since the 1970s and is more prevalent than ever today.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/energy-conservation-measure-p01] The US-based organization EVO (Efficiency Valuation Organization) has created a set of guidelines for ESCOs to adhere to in evaluating the savings achieved by ECMs.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/energy-conservation-measure-p01] These guidelines are called the International Performance Measurement and Verification Protocol (IPMVP).
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/energy-conservation-measure-p01] Energy efficiency can also be achieved by upgrading certain aspects of existing buildings.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/energy-conservation-measure-p01] Making thermal improvements by adding insulation to crawl spaces and ensuring no leaks achieves an efficient building envelope, reducing the need for mechanical systems to heat and cool the space.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/energy-conservation-measure-p01] High-performance insulation is also supported by adding double/triple-glazed windows to minimize heat transmission.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/energy-conservation-measure-p01] A window windcatcher can reduce the total energy use of a building by 23.3%.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/energy-conservation-measure-p01] Paint colors and new paint technologies can conserve energy.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/energy-conservation-measure-p01] Energy conservation through users' behaviors requires understanding household occupants' lifestyle, social, and behavioral factors in analyzing energy consumption.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/energy-conservation-measure-p01] Replacing existing appliances with newer and more efficient ones leads to energy efficiency as less energy is wasted throughout.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/energy-conservation-measure-p01] Overall, energy efficiency behaviors are identified more with one-time, cost-incurring investments in efficient appliances and retrofits, while energy curtailment behaviors include repetitive, low-cost energy-saving efforts.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/energy-conservation-measure-p01] To identify and optimize residential energy use, conventional and behavioral economics, technology adoption theory and attitude-based decision-making, social and environmental psychology, and sociology must be analyzed.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/energy-conservation-measure-p01] The techno-economic and psychological literature analysis focuses on the individual attitude, behavior, and choice/context/external conditions.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/energy-conservation-measure-p01] In contrast, the sociological literature relies more on the energy consumption practices shaped by the social, cultural, and economic factors in a dynamic setting.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/energy-conservation-measure-p01] Many steps can be taken toward energy conservation and efficiency when designing new buildings.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/energy-conservation-measure-p01] In passive solar building designs, windows, walls, and floors are made to collect, store, and distribute solar energy in the form of heat in the winter and reject solar heat in the summer.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/energy-conservation-measure-p01] The key to designing a passive solar building is to best take advantage of the local climate.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/energy-conservation-measure-p01] Elements to be considered include window placement and glazing type, thermal insulation, thermal mass, and shading.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/energy-conservation-measure-p01] Optimizing daylighting can decrease energy waste from incandescent bulbs, windows, and balconies, allow natural ventilation, reduce the need for heating and cooling, low flow mixers aid in water conservation, and upgrade to Energy star rated appliances consume less energy.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/energy-conservation-measure-p01] Designing a building according to LEED guidelines while incorporating smart home technology can help save a lot of energy and money in the long run.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/energy-conservation-measure-p01] Passive solar design techniques can be applied most easily to new buildings, but existing buildings can be retrofitted.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/energy-conservation-measure-p01] Mainly, energy conservation is achieved by modifying user habits or providing an energy-saving recommendation of curtailing an appliance or scheduling it to low-price energy tariff hours.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/energy-conservation-measure-p01] Besides changing user habits and appliance control, identifying irrelevant appliances concerning user activities in smart homes saves energy.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/energy-conservation-measure-p01] Smart home technology can advise users on energy-saving strategies according to their behavior, encouraging behavioral change that leads to energy conservation.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/energy-conservation-measure-p01] This guidance includes reminders to turn off lights, leakage sensors to prevent plumbing issues, running appliances on off-peak hours, and smart sensors that save energy.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/energy-conservation-measure-p01] Such technology learns user-appliance activity patterns, gives a complete overview of various energy-consuming appliances, and can provide guidance to improve these patterns to contribute to energy conservation.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/energy-conservation-measure-p01] It can strategically schedule appliances to the energy-efficient mode, or plan to work during off-peak hours.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/energy-conservation-measure-p01] This usually leads to appliance curtailment in which an appliance is either scheduled to work another time or is turned off.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/energy-conservation-measure-p01] Appliance curtailment involves appliance recognition, activity-appliances model, unattended appliance detection, and energy conservation service.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/energy-conservation-measure-p01] The appliance recognition module detects active appliances to identify the activities of smart home users.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/energy-conservation-measure-p01] After identifying users' activities, the association between the functional appliances and user activities is established.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/energy-conservation-measure-p01] The unattended appliance detection module looks for active appliances but is unrelated to user activity.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/energy-conservation-measure-p01] These functional appliances waste energy and can be turned off by providing recommendations to the user.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/energy-conservation-measure-p01] Users can give weight to certain appliances that increase user comfort while conserving energy.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/energy-conservation-measure-p01] Energy consumption models of energy consumption of appliances and the level of comfort they create can balance priorities among smart home comfort levels and energy consumption.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/energy-conservation-measure-p01] According to Kashimoto, Ogura, Yamamoto, Yasumoto, and Ito, the energy supply reduces based on the historical state of the appliance and increases according to the comfort level requirement of the user, leading to a targeted energy-saving ratio.
[src:energy-management-system-building-management/energy-conservation-measure-p01] Scenarios-based energy consumption can be employed as a strategy for energy conservation, with each scenario encompassing a specific set of rules for energy consumption.
